<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Factory Orders Increase in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Orders to U.S. factories
increased by 0.2 percent to a record level in July following a big
gain in June, a sign that the U.S. economy grew at a brisk pace
this summer.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. commerce Department reported today that factory orders
advanced to a seasonally adjusted 330.3 billion dollars in July
followed a 1.7 percent jump in June.
</P>
<P>
The June's figure was revised up from an earlier estimate of
1.2 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
The increase of factory orders in the month resulted largely
from gains in non-durable goods. Orders for non-durable goods
increased 0.9 percent with food products, textiles and rubber and
plastic items seeing the biggest gains.
</P>
<P>
However, orders for durable goods -- items expected to last at
least three years -- fell 0.3 percent in July, the worst in seven
months.
</P>
<P>
The decline occurred not only in transportation but also in
electronic and electrical equipment. The volatile transportation
sector declined by 3.5 percent. An increase in orders for cars and
trucks wasn't enough to offset a decline in aircraft.
</P>
<P>
But orders rose 6.6 percent for industrial machinery, with
engines and turbines registering a 29.1 percent jump. Orders rose
3.7 percent for primary metals such as steel.
</P>
<P>
The backlog of unfilled orders decreased by 0.5 percent to a
seasonally adjusted 521.4 billion dollars, the first drop since
April.
</P>
<P>
Shipments, a measure of current production, rose 1.4 percent to
332.9 billion dollars. And inventories also increased by 0.5
percent to 447 billion dollars in the month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
