<HEADLINE> Suicide Jerusalem Attack Casts Shadow on Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 4 (Xinhua)-- Three suspected Hamas suicide
bombings ripped through a central Jerusalem pedestrian mall today
killing six people and wounding 160 others.
</P>
<P>
The terror attack cast shadow over the pending visit to the
Middle East by U.S. Secretary of State Medeleine Albright in an
effort to rescue the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The bombings went off around 3 p.m. local time (noon GMT) in
the bustling Ben Yehuda mall in downtown Jerusalem, barely one
kilometer away from the site of the twin bombings in Mahane Yehuda
market on July 30, in which 17 were killed and 170 others wounded.
</P>
<P>
Police supsected that three suicide bombers blew them up
outside a popular cafe in seconds apart. At least six were
killed, including three suicide bombers, and over 160 wounded in
th attack.
</P>
<P>
In an anonymous call to a French news agency, Hamas, the
Islamic Resistance Movement, claimed responsibility for the attack
as it did in the Mahane Yehuda bombings.
</P>
<P>
The group threatened to carry out more attacks unless Hamas
prisoiners held by Israel were released by September 14.
</P>
<P>
Although its authenticity is yet to be confimed, Israel reacted
strongly to the bombings by immediaitely reimposing a total
closure on the Palestinian self-rule territories of West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials quickly held the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) responsible for the attack, citing its refusal to
accept the Israeli demand to crack down hard on terrorism and
dismantle its infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Illan, adviser to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, accusing PNA President Yasser Arafat of encouraging
terrorist attacks by "hugging and holding" a Hamas leader in a
Palestinian unity meeting not long ago.
</P>
<P>
For its part, the PNA condemned the bombings as criminal acts
amied at destroying the already deeply-troubled peace process, and
called on Israel to refrain from tightening sanctions against
Palestinians in the form of collective punishment.
</P>
<P>
Today's bombings came only days before Albright's arrival in
the region due on September 10 trying to bring new intiatives to
revive peace negotiations between Isreal and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
It is vividly reminicent to many people of the July 30 Mahane
Yehuda bombings, which took place on the eve of the arrival of
U.S. special envoy Dennis Ross, who subsequently put off his trip
for a week.
</P>
</TEXT>
