<HEADLINE> Chernomyrdin Urges Fight Against Tax-related Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin has called for a crack-down on tax-related crime.
</P>
<P>
At a government meeting today he said the central and local law
enforcement organs must take more positive and coordinated action
in tackling tax-related crimes, which directly threatened Russia's
economic security, the Inter-fax and Itar-Tass news agencies
reported.
</P>
<P>
The meeting severely censured the Federal Tax Police Bureau for
its inefficient work. The meeting was called to consider the role
of the bureau in fighting tax-related crimes.
</P>
<P>
Russian First Deputy Prime Minister Anatoly Chubais said the
situation in which taxation had failed to increase budget income
had not been reversed.
</P>
<P>
The state expenditure had been supported by income from
privatization and other items, said Chubais.
</P>
<P>
Anatoly Kulikov, Russian deputy prime minister and interior
minister, criticized the bureau for serious failings in appointing
leaders. He indicated that 20 chiefs of the central and local tax
police bureaus had been dismissed recently, including 10
generals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
