<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suicide Jerusalem Attack Casts Shadow on Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 4 (Xinhua)--
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the July 30 bombings, Israel imposed severe
sanctions against Palestinians, including a total closure, an
entry ban on Palestinian workers and freeze of tax revenues owed
to the PNA, to pressure the PNA to crack down on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
To pave the way for Albright's visit, Ross' four-day mediation
mission here early last month restored security ties between
Israel and the Palestinians with the presence of U.S. officials.
Palestinian police has cooperated with Israel in investigating the
July 30 bombings and in apprehending Palestinian criminals.
</P>
<P>
Israel in recent weeks reciprocated by gradually easing the
sanctions, releasing partially the frozen tax revenue funds and
allowing a limited number of Palestinian workers, merchants and
officials to enter Israel.
</P>
<P>
As Israel reinstituted the total closure and other sanctions
against Palestinians, the prospects for a breakthrough in during
Albright's visit seemed diminishing.
</P>
<P>
Both Israel and the PNA had been expecting Albright's visit in
hope of taking advantage of U.S. influence to pressure the other
side into making more compromises.
</P>
<P>
Israel demanded the PNA launch a long-term crackdown on terror
groups and their infrastructure, while the PNA insisted that
Israel firstly end the collective punishment of the Palestinian
people as a whole.
</P>
<P>
In the aftermath of today's bombings, Israel is expected to
increase pressure on the PNA on the issue of fighting terrorism
and would be more reluctant to easing the sanctions. Local reports
said Netanyahu would hold an emergency cabinet meeting soon.
</P>
<P>
However, the sanctions may backfire because of mounting tension
between the two sides and the economic hardship they inflicted on
the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
