<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Central Bank Lowers Certificates Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia, the country's
central bank, today lowered its one-month and three-month
short-term bilateral certificates (SBIS) rates by three percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
The Bank Indonesia said in a statement that the rate of the
month-long SBI was lowered from 30 percent to 27 percent, while
the rate for the three-month SBIS from 28 percent to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the SBI overnight rate remains at 15 percent, while
for one week the SBI rate is at 20 percent, two weeks at 22
percent, six months 12.125 percent, and one year remains at 12.75
percent.
</P>
<P>
The central bank raised its one month SBI rate to 30 percent
and its three-month SBI rate to 28 percent on August 19.
</P>
<P>
The rate increase was aimed at stabilizing the rupiah currency
against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
To curb the rupiah fluctuation, the government introduced a
tight monetary policy and raised the SBI rates along with the
temporary halt of the purchase money market securities (SBPUS) by
the central bank.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the lowering of SBI rates aims to show
the government's promise to relax the tight money policy in
stages.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Mar'ie Muhammad said on Wednesday that to
prevent the currency turmoil from leading to an economic crisis,
Indonesia needs to take credible proactive measures that will
anticipate future problems.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the rupiah continued to lose ground despite the
package of measures announced Wednesday by the finance minister.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah fell to 3,030/3,040 against the U.S. dollar at
mid-afternoon trading today.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has fallen more than 10 percent in the past month
and nearly 23 percent since January following offshore speculative
attacks on the currency and a rush by local companies to hedge
their foreign borrowings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
