<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, September 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- At least four people were killed and 100 others
wounded in three consecutive bomb explosions in down town
Jerusalem Thursday afternoon with many casualties and extensive
damages.
</P>
<P>
The explosions went off in the crowded Ben Yehuda Street
pedestrian mall at about 15:00 local time (noon GMT).
(Jerusalem-Explosions)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM-- Israel reimposed Thursday a total closure of the
Palestinian self-rule territories after three suspected suicide
bombings in central Jerusalem killed at least five people and
wounded 140 others.
</P>
<P>
The closure order was given by Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai after he learned about the bombings, which were
claimed by the anti-Israeli Palestinian organization, the Islamic
Resistance Movement (Hamas). (Israel-Jerusalem-Bombings)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi newspaper "Al-Thawara" Thursday called on the
Arabs to get united against the Israeli-U.S.-Turkish alliance.
</P>
<P>
Since the late 1970s, Turkey has been playing a dangerous game
which is part of a long-term U.S.-Israeli plan designed to put
pressure on nations of the region by keeping them under constant
threat of aggression, the paper said.
(Iraq-Turkish-Israeli Alliance)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin will dispatch a
special envoy to the Middle East within the next few days on a
fresh mission to restore the peace march to its right track, the
Middle East News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The mission of the presidential envoy falls as part of Russia's
position as co-sponsor in the Mideast peace process that was
initiated with Madrid, MENA quoted a Russian high-ranking official
as saying. (Egypt-Russia-Mideast Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Union (EU) has called for the
submission of energy projects eligible for co-financing under an
international cooperation program.
</P>
<P>
The EU move, through the regional alliance's executive body,
the European Commission, is also designed to boost cooperation
with non-EU member countries, media reports said today.
(EU-Cooperation-Projects)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SINGAPORE -- The Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) of China, Tung Chee Hwa, arrived here
today on a three-day visit at the invitation of Singapore Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong.
</P>
<P>
Tung flew in the Singapore Changi International Airport from
Malaysia, where he just concluded a two-day visit, his first
overseas trip since assuming office on July 1.
(Singapore-Tung Chee Hwa-Arrival)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- More and more Lebanese officials and politicians
slammed U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright for her failure
to include Lebanon in her itinerary to the Middle East, local
media reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Albright's tour, which is to start next Tuesday, will include
Israel, Palestinian-held territory, Egypt, Jordan, Syria and Saudi
Arabia. (Lebanon-US-Albright)  
</P>
</TEXT>
