<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Navy Gets Two Corvette Warships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Two corvette warships
arrived today at the Royal Malaysian Navy (RMN) base in Lumut,
northwestern Malaysia, the Malaysian national news agency Bernama
reported.
</P>
<P>
The RMN will get two more corvette warships in early 1999, in
addition to the two -- KD Laksamana Hang Nadim and KD Laksamana
Tun Abdul Jamil, Bernama said quoting Defense Minister Syed Hamid
Albar as saying at a news conference in Lumut.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister said the warships are part of efforts to
modernize the national fleet in stages.
</P>
<P>
"The purchases of the fast warships are not meant as
competition with our neighbors but for the mutual defense of all
for the future generations," Syed Hamid was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The two corvettes are equipped with advanced weapons systems
and radar, with a range of up to 180 kilometers, and have four
missile launchers and sonar for detecting submarines, he said.
</P>
<P>
A crew of 56 including officers for the two warships who
underwent training in the use of the sophisticated equipment
onboard for nearly a year arrived onboard the two warships.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the four warships are 10 years old but have
never been used in warfare.  
</P>
</TEXT>
