<HEADLINE> EU Committee Urges Debate on Privacy Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A European Parliament
committee is seeking a debate on action at European Union (EU)
level to curb press intrusion, following the death of Princess
Diana in a car crash in Paris last weekend.
</P>
<P>
The media and culture committee wants the debate to be held
during the Parliament's session in Strasbourg, France, this month,
said a press release issued by the Socialist Group of the
Parliament here today.
</P>
<P>
"There needs to be a full, democratic debate on privacy and the
media." said Socialist spokeswoman on the committee, Carole Tongue.
</P>
<P>
"The question of how to strike a balance between freedom of
information and the right to privacy is a very serious issue. We
need a proper period of reflection and an informed public debate,"
she added.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the issue had become an international problem
which required attention at an international level.
</P>
<P>
"Diana was a powerful, compassionate force for changing
attitudes, most recently in her crusade against landmines. We owe
it to her memory to reflect on attitudes towards privacy," she
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
