<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Peace Initiatives Despite Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 4 (Xinhua) -- There are new peace
initiatives by senior Rahanwein clan delegates and officials from
Hussein Aidid's government despite severe and sporadic guerrilla
hit and run fighting between the forces of Hussein Mohamed Aidid
and the Rahanwein Resistance Army, RRA, in the southwestern
regions of Bay and Bakol.
</P>
<P>
A top level delegation led by Sheikh Mukhtar Mohamed Hussein,
an 85 year old and well respected Rahanwein elder, and Mr Abdi
Warsame Issak, a minister from Hussein Aidid's government, have
left for Bay and Bakol regions this week in an attempt of
pacifying the warring sides battling over the control of Baidoa
and Huddor.
</P>
<P>
The delegation of Sheikh Mukhtar, the former spokesman of
Somalia's first civilian parliament, encouraged by Hussein
Mohamed Aidid have already been meeting elders and intellectuals
from the Rahanwein communities in the towns of Bay and Huddor
since Monday this week. Radio South Mogadishu supporting Hussein
Mohamed Aidid which spoke about the new peace initiatives has
characterized these meetings as a step forward in pacifying the
brothers.
</P>
<P>
There are also reports making the whole peace process as
controversial. Representatives from the Rahanwein Resistance Army
in north Mogadishu have characterized the peace efforts backed by
Hussein Aidid as nonsense. A spokesman for the RRA, Mr Mohamed
Ali Aden Qalinle, said there can be no peace in these regions as
long as Hussein Aidid's men are in control of the towns of Baidoa
and Bakol.
</P>
<P>
Mr Qalinle said the efforts of Sheikh Mukhtar can bring about
no fruits since he's not independent for his moves and decisions
as he put it. Mr Qalinle furthermore said his faction doesn't
oppose to mediation, "we welcome any peace initiative launched by
the neutral clans of Somalia," said Mr Qalinle.
</P>
<P>
The sporadic fighting which claimed the lives of many and
displaced hundreds of families from these two regions had
likewise been making nervous the faction led by Hussein Mohamed
Aidid, especially the guerrilla fighting in the area of Baidoa
which is vital for the safety and control of the only tarmac
airport, Ballidogle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
