<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Accuses ECOMOG of Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The military junta in Sierra
Leone today accused th west African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG)
of discriminate shelling that killed civilians.
</P>
<P>
A series of bombardment by ECOMOG troops left "50 dead and 17
seriously wounded", said a spokesman of the junta, quoted by the
British Broadcasting Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Accusing ECOMOG troops of continuous bombarding for the past
40 hours, the spokesman particularly mentioned three that took
place at midnight Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Three shells landed yesterday (night), one at 11:30, one at
11:45 and one 7:30 this morning," which led to the death and
injuries on innocent civilians, said the spokeman of the Armed
Forces Revolutionary Council (AFRC), Sierra Leone's current
supreme governing body.
</P>
<P>
AFRC, led by Major Johnny Koroma, was set up after the May 25
coup that toppled the legitimate government of ousted President
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG was dispatched to the Sierra Leonean capital of
Freetown in the wake of the coup in an attempt to restore
Kabbah's government.
</P>
<P>
Repeated clashes have been reported between the ECOMOG troops
and AFRC soldiers.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG now still holds the Lungi international airport near
Freetown, where the alleged bombardment was launched.
</P>
<P>
However, ECOMOG Force Commander Major-General Victor Malu has
denied the accusation, saying: "We are not firing any civilian
position" in an area in Freetown whose name he did not known.
</P>
<P>
"Any firing that you know in Sierra Leone is done because we
fire upon and we have to return fire at the motion of getting our
defensive," Malu said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a demonstration against ECOMOG allegedly led by
Nigeria was staged by civilians in Freetown today.
</P>
<P>
According to a BBC report, many demonstrators were waving
banners and singing songs in support of the AFRC administration.
</P>
<P>
They appealed to the international community and the United
Nations to help put a stop to what they called "Nigerians are
kept to make Sierra Leone a puppet state".
</P>
<P>
The demonstration was prompted by the report of shelling by
the ECOMOG troops based in the Lungi international airport,
according to the BBC.  
</P>
</TEXT>
