<HEADLINE> Kenya's NCEC Announces Strikes, Demonstrations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's opposition umbrella
body, the National Convention Executive Council (NCEC), today
called national strikes and demonstrations in a bid to increase
pressure on the government for constitutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
The countrywide strikes and demonstrations were scheduled for
September 17, September 18, October 8 and October 9, NCEC senior
member Willy Mutunga said at a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
He said the NCEC, set up in April to coordinate the
opposition's reform campaign, is also to hold a rally in Kisumu,
ashore Lake Victoria as the third-largest city in the country, on
Sunday and here on October 10, a public holiday.
</P>
<P>
Traditionally, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi, now aged 73
and in power since 1978, makes a public speech on October 10
annually.
</P>
<P>
"NCEC calls upon Kenyans to prepare themselves for protracted
and intensified mass action," said Mutunga, claiming that only
pressure from people could force the government towards political
changes for so-called fair and free elections.
</P>
<P>
However, he added that "we must emphasize that mass action
does not mean violence. Those who engage in disruptive violence,
looting and other unlawful acts are agent provocateurs and
anti-reform."
</P>
<P>
One day earlier, the NCEC dismissed the inter-parties
parliamentary group talks on reforms dialogue among members of
parliament from both the ruling Kenya African National Union and
opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 parliamental members held a meeting last
Thursday and resolved to form a 13-member inter-parties
parliamentary body to replace NCEC to spearhead reform talks
between KANU and the opposition.
</P>
<P>
But NCEC charged that the Kenyan parliament does not represent
all Kenyan people as KANU enjoys an absolute majority.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, KANU reiterated it will not hold dialogue with the
NCEC as the latter is unregistered, insisting that the reform
talks should only be undertaken within legal framework.
</P>
<P>
KANU will open its National Delegate Conference on September
16 over reform talks and the forthcoming general elections. At
the KANU conference before the first multi-party election in
1992, Moi was elected as KANU's sole presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
Political atmosphere has been tightening in the eastern
African country following several rounds of violent clashes
between the government and the opposition since May, the key loan
cut by the International Monetary Fund and killings on the Coast.
</P>
<P>
Moi has recently claimed that he would soon announce the poll
date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
