<HEADLINE> Beira Corridor Group to Be Wound Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Beira Corridor Group (BCG)
will wind up its operations at the end of the year as members
feel the organisation has successfully fulfilled its mandate, the
Zimbabwe News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Beira Corridor is a railway and road network running between
the Zimbabwean eastern border town of Mutare to the Mozambican
port city of Beira.
</P>
<P>
BCG chairman John Laurie said on Wednesday members had
unanimously agreed to close it down at the firm's annual general
meeting held in Harare in August.
</P>
<P>
Formed as a business sector lobby in 1986, BCG's original
mandate was to ensure the Beira Corridor was available to
importers and exporters as an alternative to south African
routes.
</P>
<P>
"BCG's 280 member companies, mostly from Zimbabwe, made it
clear at the annual general meeting that they felt this objective
had been amply achieved, and that the Beira Corridor had indeed
become an economic and efficient alternative to the more distant
and more expensive south African port," said Laurie in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Laurie said with the successful launching of the Maputo
Development Corridor early in 1996, BCG spearheaded efforts to
transform the focus of the Beira Corridor from a transport route
into a development corridor."
</P>
<P>
"The concept of a development corridor, based on the fact that
there already exists a sound infrastructural spine, required the
establishment of a formal government and business sector
structure designed to remove impediments to investment and trade,
and to stimulate increased investor interest," said Laurie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Continues Preparing for Albright's Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Despite today's suicide
bombings in Jerusalem, Israel is continuing preparing for the
visit to the region by United States Secretary Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry said in a statement that it is continuing
contact with Israeli Embassy in Washington and the U.S. Embassy in
Tel Aviv on arranging Albright's mission.
</P>
<P>
Three powerful bomb explosions ripped through central
Jerusalem's Ben Yehuda pedestrian mall at 3 p.m. local time (noon
GMT), claiming at least seven people and injuring 165 others.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government is reportedly reconsidering Albright's trip
to the Middle East in the wake of the attack, partly because of
the seven-day mourning period for the victims in Israel.
</P>
<P>
But she is expected to proceed with the much-awaited trip,
which will focus on rescuing the deeply-troubled
Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the ministry had briefed all Israeli
diplomatic missions abroad on today's bombings, in a bid to win
international support for Israeli stance on fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Israeli militant group Islamic Resistance Movement
(Hamas) claimed responsibility for the attack as it did in the
previous one on July 30 when two suicide bombings went off in
Jerusalem's Mahane Yehuda market, not far away from today's site,
killing 17 people and wounding 170 others.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Cabinet Secretary Abdel
Rahman condemned the attackers for trying to prevent Albright's
visit. He also offered to resume full security cooperation with
Israel in fighting terrorism, a condition set by Israel for
restarting the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In response to the bombing attack, Israel immediately reimposed
the total closure of the Palestinian self-rule territories of West
Bank and Gaza Strip, which has been partially eased in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials strongly denounced the PNA for failing to
respond to the Israeli demand on cracking down on terrorism, and
held it responsible for the attack.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, during a visit to
the wounded in a hospital, said that unless the PNA changed its
attitude toward the terrorism, the peace process cannot continue.
</P>
<P>
"We will not continue on this route of periodic bouts of
terrorism," vowed Netanyahu, who is to consult with senior
security officials tonight to formulate further reaction to the
attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
