<HEADLINE>                  Three Photographers Surrender to Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Three photographers today
surrendered to police for having chased the Mercedes car of the
late Princess of Wales Diana Spencer last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The photographers, who knew that they had been recognized by
police, went to the police ``simultaneously'' and are now detained
by police, said Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
Identified as employees of two specialized photo agencies, they
could be brought to a judge for questioning in a second step of
the legal proceeding.
</P>
<P>
Six photographers and one press motorcyclist were put under
judicial investigation on Tuesday by Judge Herve Stephan of the
Paris Investigation Court for ``involuntary homicide and
involuntary injury'' and ``non-assistance to persons in danger''
in a traffic accident which killed Diana, her friend Egyptian
millionaire Dodi al Fayed and their chauffeur Henri Paul.
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted investigators of the anti-riot Criminal Brigade of
the French Police Force as saying that they have found ``a
succession of extremely grave, coordinating and sad events'' which
are linked to the accident.
</P>
<P>
The Criminal Brigade said that some photographers could have
taken pictures of Diana injured in the accident and then fled away
before the arrival of police agents, as they have seized some
photos ``ready to be sold in the market'' by photo agencies.
</P>
<P>
Laurent Sola, the boss of the LS Press Agency which is a target
of police, said he sold the pictures within five hours after
the accident took place.
</P>
<P>
Police are continuing to investigate the situation around the
departure of Diana from the Ritz Hotel, which they described as
being under ``the climate of precipitation of tension'' at that
time.
</P>
<P>
Police found that Henri Paul, the 41-year-old security
assistant chief of the hotel who drove the Mercedes, was drunk and
that he did not qualify for the job of driving the super-powerful
limousine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
