<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Satisfied with German's Position: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus today expressed
satisfaction with statement by German's Foreign Minister
Klaus Kinkel on Cyprus' prospects for accession to the European
Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Manolis Christofides made the statement
at his daily press briefing here after Kinkel held a meeting with
his visiting Cypriot counterpart Ioannis Kasoulides in Bonn
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel was quoted as saying after the meeting that Cyprus-EU
accession talks will begin as agreed, six months after the end of
the Intergovernmental Conference.
</P>
<P>
However, he told Kasoulides that "it is to Cyprus' benefit to
have the northern part of the island (Turkish Cypriots) involved
in all negotiations held."
</P>
<P>
The German foreign minister said his country will contribute
toward efforts to defuse tensions between Greece and Turkey, a
factor he described as important to reaching a settlement in
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel said he will discuss the issue in the upcoming talks he
will have with his Turkish counterpart Ismail Cem and Turkish
Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus applied for full EU membership in 1990. The EU
reaffirmed its decision in July that accession talks with Cyprus
will begin early next year.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.N.-sponsored two rounds of direct talks between
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash in the U.S. and Switzerland in the past two months
ended in failure because the Turkish Cypriot side refused to
further negotiate a settlement unless the EU postpones the
accession talks with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel expressed regret over the fact that the U.N.-sponsored
direct talks were not successful and stressed that "the momentum
of these talks cannot be lost."
</P>
<P>
The German minister said he has accepted an invitation from
his Cypriot counterpart to visit the island in spring.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Kasoulides reiterated the Cypriot president's
dedication to negotiations for a settlement to the Cyprus
problem, saying that the Cyprus government considers the
island's entry into the EU as "absolutely necessary" in order to
achieve a speedy solution to the political problem.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkey sent its troops and took over the
northern third of the island in the wake of a failed coup seeking
union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
