<HEADLINE> Pro-Kurdish Activists Detained in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkish police detained 21
pro-Kurdish activists, including 18 foreigners, in the largest
city of Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
A police statement said these people were taken into custody
when they tried to hold a press conference in defiance of a
warning.
</P>
<P>
About 270 activists were barred by the Istanbul police from
giving a press conference Wednesday and were warned that their
planned press conference would constitute an illegal act.
</P>
<P>
Two diplomats from Italy and Britain in Ankara were set free
afterwards, the police said.
</P>
<P>
The foreigners are from Denmark, Spain, Germany, Italy and
Britain. They entered Turkey under a "Peace Train" plan, initiated
by pro-Kurdish Europeans.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government tried to block the plan, but some
activists managed their way into Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Kurdish issue is a long-standing problem puzzling the
Turkish government. Since 1984, It has been fighting the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party which seeks to establish an
independent state in southeastern Turkey. 
