<HEADLINE> Clinton Condemns Jerusalem Bombings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton on
Thursday condemned bombings at a downtown Jerusalem shopping mall,
saying it was not "tolerated."
</P>
<P>
Speaking from his vacation resort in Martha's Vineyard, Mass.,
Clinton declared that Secretary of State Madeleine Albright would
go as scheduled to the Middle East next week and would take with
her the message "that terror will not be tolerated."
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that the perpetrators of this attack intended to
kill both innocent people and the peace process itself. They must
not be allowed to succeed," Clinton said at a hastily arranged
news conference.
</P>
<P>
He said he was certain an overwhelming majority of Palestinians
and Israelis "yearn for an end to violence and for the start of
lasting peace."
</P>
<P>
"Everything possible must be done to stop them. The peace
process can only move forward in a secure environment," he said,
adding "this is a message that Secretary Albright will emphasize
when she travels to the region next week." 
</P>
