<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Greek Defense Minister's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government
welcomed today Greek Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos'
statement that Turkey's attempted strike at Russian anti-aircraft
missiles in Cyprus would cause war.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Manolis Christofides made the remark at
his daily press briefing while commenting on the Greek minister's
statement during his visit to London.
</P>
<P>
The Greek minister said in an interview over London Greek Radio
that the Cyprus problem is not Turkey's internal problem and
threats have no place and are rejected not only by Greece and
Cyprus, but by the entire international community.
</P>
<P>
On how Greece reacts to Turkey's threats to attack the S-300
missiles, the minister said "I would advise our neighbor not
to slide along dangerous avenues to manipulating foreign
matters."
</P>
<P>
Referring to what Greece would do in case Turkey follows
through with its threats, Tsohatzopoulos reiterated that the
joint defense pact between Greece and Cyprus is there to be
implemented. Any attack by Turkey against Cyprus is casus belli,
the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed an agreement with Russia early this year to
purchase S-300 missile systems in an effort to defend its
military bases. The delivery of the missiles is expected to be
done by autumn next year.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has repeatedly threatened to strike them once they are
installed in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Under a joint defense pact agreed by the governments of Cyprus
and Greece in 1993, Greece will come to aid of Cyprus if the
island is attacked militarily.
</P>
<P>
Athens has warned Ankara that any further advance of the
Turkish troops toward the Cypriot government-controlled southern
part of the island would mean war between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Greek defense minister expressed the hope that
the peace process in Cyprus bears fruit and direct negotiations
between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides aimed at solving the
Cyprus problem will continue following the Cyprus presidential
elections early next year.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both NATO allies, are at odds over this
eastern Mediterranean island, which has been divided since 1974
when Turkey sent troops and took over 37 percent of the island in
the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
