<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Following are business briefs
from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Trade volume between Jordan and Syria exceeded 130
million U.S. dollars in 1996, a Jordanian official said here today.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Mustafa Khreisat, director of Jordan's
pavilion at the current Damascus International Exhibition in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Khreisat said trade balance in 1996 was in favor of Syria, when
Jordan imported some 90 million dollars worth of goods whereas
exports valued at about 40 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's most important imports from Syria are ready-made
clothes while cement tops Jordan's exports to Syria, he said.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Trade volume between Syria and Egypt in 1996 rose
to 252 million Egyptian pounds (about 74 million dollars),
according to the Egyptian Embassy here today.
</P>
<P>
This was about 88 percent up from five years ago when the
figure stood at 134 million pounds (about 39 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
A breakdown of last year's trade volume showed that Syrian
exports register at 52 million pounds (about 15 million dollars)
and Egyptian exports to Syria 200 million pounds (about 59 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
An Egyptian commercial attache who was here attending the
current Damascus international exhibition said Syrian exports to
Egypt include tobacco, lintel, spices and certain plants.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is exporting to Syria rice, oil, lubricants, tourist
buses, medicine and chemicals, he added.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed by the two countries in 1961, 19
Syrian and 20 Egyptian commodities are exempt from customs duties.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The gross foreign reserves of the Bank of Lebanon,
the country's central bank, rose slightly by 1.5 million dollars
in the second half of August to 6.598 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese newspaper the Beirut Times said Wednesday that
gross reserves rose by 22 million dollars in the first half of
August to 6.597 billion dollars, including commercial banks' net
foreign exchange deposits with the central bank.
</P>
<P>
According to banking sources, net reserves climed to 5 billion
dollars at the end of June 1997 compared with 4.015 billion
dollars at the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon will gain 60 million dollars in soft loans
from Italy to finance the country's development projects in
impoverished rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper The Beirut Times reported that the loans will
be spent on health care and development projects in eastern
Baalkek-Hermel region, three waste water treatment plants and a
water supply system in other areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
