<HEADLINE> SADC Members urged to Promote Social Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) today called on its
member states to improve social stability while making available
a sustaining economic growth in the region, reported Zambia News
Agency (ZANA).
</P>
<P>
Alfred Nzo, Chairman of the SADC council of ministers, made
the statement at the council's meeting which opened this morning
in Blantyre, Malawi.
</P>
<P>
Nzo, also South African foreign minister, said that SADC had
provided the frame work to sustain economic growth in the region
and all member states should apply themselves to these
challenges.
</P>
<P>
The region's gross domestic product has jumped by more than 6
percent since the inception of the Southern African Development
Co-ordination Conference (SADCC), he noted, urging that the rate
be consolidated by promoting the social sector in the region.
</P>
<P>
The council chairman elaborated that the agricultural sector
did very well in the last farming season when the region recorded
17.4 million tons of maize despite of serious floods.
</P>
<P>
The SADC council of ministers are also expected to recommend
the adoption of a declaration of the ban on anti-personnel mines
to the forthcoming SADC summit to be held Monday.
</P>
<P>
The SADC council will also consider the applications from the
Seychelles and the Democratic Republic of Congo which have
indicated their willingness to join the 12-member regional body,
ZANA reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
