<HEADLINE> Jordan Condemns New Explosions in Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Jordan condemned today's suicide
bomb explosions in downtown West Jerusalem that killed at least
seven people, including three suspected Hamas bombers, and wounded
165 others.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's King Hussein made a telephone call this evening to
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to condemn the bombings,
saying Jordan is against such a terrorist action.
</P>
<P>
The king hoped that the new explosions would not adversely
affect the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The explosions were plotted by a small number of
fundamentalists who wanted to ruin the peace which was just what
most people wanted, the king said over the phone.
</P>
<P>
The previous explosions took place in Jerusalem on July 30
killing 17 people and injuring 170 others, devastating the peace
process which has been stalled since Israel broke ground for the
building of a controversial Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem in
March.
</P>
<P>
Today`s explosions prompted the Israeli government to reimpose
the total closure on West Bank and Gaza Strip which has been
partially eased during the past weeks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jordanian Minister of State for Information Affairs
Samir Mutawe released a statement to condemn the suicide terror
attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
