<HEADLINE> Over 27,000 UNITA Forces Demobilized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Minister of Assistance
and Reinsertation Albina Malungo said today that over 27,000
militiamen of the former rebel movement National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) have been demobilized.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement to the press after attending the meeting
of the Joint Commission on Angolan Peace Process.
</P>
<P>
The commission was satisfactory about the progress of UNITA's
"quick demobilization", Malungo noted, adding that the
demobilized fighters are now forbidden to leave the assembly
area.
</P>
<P>
However, he believed that the issue could only be completely
solved when national authorities are re-established in all the
areas occupied by UNITA.
</P>
<P>
The issue was discussed Wednesday by the joint commission,
after which its spokesman Higino Carneiro said, since the work
was restored at the end of August, only 31 of the total 100 areas
occupied by UNITA was facilitated with national authorities. He
blamed UNITA for setting up obstacles to the task, and denounced
the rebel movement for it.
</P>
<P>
Owing to the pressure from the international community and
mediations from various sectors, the Angolan Peace Process which
was halted for as long as four months, has again made progress,
with the renewed demobilization of UNITA militiamen and the
re-establishment of national authorities in UNITA-occupied areas,
although the pace has been very slow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
