<HEADLINE> Turkey's Welfare Party Facing Closure Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Constitutional Court
decided today to grant the pro-Islamic Welfare Party (RP) an
extra month to prepare its defense against closure charges.
</P>
<P>
With additional 30 days, RP, led by Turkey's former prime
minister Necmettin Erbakan, is to submit its defense statement to
the Court before October 6.
</P>
<P>
On August 6, the pro-Islamic Party asked the Constitutional
Court for an extra 60 days to complete its defense statement.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Chief Prosecutor Vural Savas filed in May a closure
case against RP with Turkey's supreme judicial organ on the
grounds that it supports Islamic fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
According to Turkish law, Erbakan and other senior RP
officials would be barred from politics for five years if their
Party were closed down.
</P>
<P>
It is rumored that Erbakan might resign from RP to avoid being
shut out of political life. But it was denied and put as
"groundless" by RP deputy chairman Sevket Kazan.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan has been criticized for not curbing the expanding
fundamentalism in this secular country during his tenure as prime
minister before June 18 when the Turkish military forced him to
resign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
