<HEADLINE> France Tries 26 Members of Turkish Drug Trafficking Ring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A court in the northeastern
French city of Metz put on trial this week 26 drug traffickers,
including 16 Turkish nationals, who are described as extremely
violent and had smuggled 150 kilograms of heroin from Turkey to
France and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Public Prosecutor Brigitte Garrigues today recommended 10 years
of jail against the heads of the ring, and nine years to six
months of jail against their accomplices, plus 94.01 million
francs (about 15 million U.S. dollars) of fines, reported Agence
France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
She also suggested a banning of the 16 Turkish nationals of the
ring from definitive or limited stay in France.
</P>
<P>
French police broke the ring in November 1995 after Jean Marc
Kappes, one of the heads of the group, informed against other
members, said AFP.
</P>
<P>
Garrigues said the group was exceptionally dangerous and acted
under "an immense climate of violence." 
</P>
</TEXT>
