<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brady Law Prevents 173,000 Handgun Sales in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A new analysis by the U.S.
Justice Department shows the Brady Bill has prevented 173,000
illegal handgun sales since it was enacted in February 1994.
</P>
<P>
About 70,000 sales were blocked in 1996 alone, and overall, the
bill has kept 250,000 firearms of all types out of the hands of
felons, the mentally ill and other unqualified potential
gun-owners.
</P>
<P>
An earlier report by the department's Bureau of Justice
Statistics, "Presale Firearms Checks," estimated that 6,600
applications for firearms of all types were rejected by dealers
each month between the advent of Brady background checks and July
1997.
</P>
<P>
The Brady law requires federally-licensed dealers to submit
handgun purchase applications for background checks on the buyers.
</P>
<P>
The law is named after former press secretary James Brady, who
was seriously wounded in the assassination attempt on the then
President Ronald Reagan. It was passed in 1993 after bitter
congressional battles and was strongly opposed by the National
Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
Last June, the Supreme Court ruled the federal government could
not order the states to perform the background checks. Almost all
states, however, continue to check voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
Last year, dealers throughout the United States obtained
background checks on almost 2.6 million handgun applications --
about 2.7 percent were rejected.
</P>
<P>
About 47,000 handgun sales were rejected because applicants had
been indicted or convicted of felonies; 4,200 because buyers were
fugitives from justice; 3,900 because the buyers were excluded
under state laws; 2,700 because the buyers were under court
restraining orders; and 1,000 because the buyers were mental
patients.
</P>
<P>
The rest were blocked for various reasons: some were juveniles,
others were illegal aliens or dishonorably discharged armed
services members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Sees Record Number of Bankruptcies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The number of corporate
bankruptcies in Germany reached a new record in the first half of
1997 despite increasing signs indicating that the country's
economic recovery is well underway, official figures showed today.
</P>
<P>
According to data released today by the Federal Statistics
Office in Wiesbaden, there were 2,620 corporate bankruptcies
reported in June, up 25.5 percent from the level a year ago. The
most dramatic increase was registered in eastern Germany, where
corporate bankruptcies shot up 44 percent from the same month last
year.
</P>
<P>
With the June figures, the number of corporate bankruptcies in
Germany in the first half of 1997 reached 13,598, up 8.8 percent
on the same period last year. The eastern half of Germany reported
4,033 bankruptcies in the first six months, a increase of 11.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the latest bankruptcy figures were an indication
that the current export-driven economic upswing in Germany had
benefited mainly large companies. The numerous small and
medium-sized companies in the country were increasingly at a
disadvantage to compete with low-labor-cost nations on the world
market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Accuses S. Leonean Junta of Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria today accused of the
military junta in Sierra Leone of launching offensive attack on
the positions of west African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) there,
resulting in the deaths of many civilians.
</P>
<P>
A Defense Headquarters statement said a lot of civilian
casualties have been reported today as sporadic fire was used
against innocent citizens and ECOMOG positions in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
"Following a meeting of the Sierra Leonean junta and the
military commanders yesterday, the junta early today launched an
offensive against the ECOMOG troops and innocent citizens," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It also accused the junta of planting landmines, saying that
it is shame to do so "while the world over is condemning the use
of landmines."
</P>
<P>
The statement came after the junta's accusation earlier today
of shells fired by ECOMOG at midnight Wednesday that killed 50
civilians and seriously wounded 17 in the Sierra Leone capital of
Freetown.
</P>
<P>
However, ECOMOG Force Commander Victor Malu has denied the
accusation, saying that ECOMOG did not fire any "civilian
population area".
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG troops were sent to Sierra Leone following the May 25
coup that ousted the legitimate government led by President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Exchange of fires between ECOMOG troops and soldiers loyal to
the junta has been reported.
</P>
<P>
As the junta refused the international demand to step down
with a four-year transition plan, west African leaders last week
ordered ECOMOG to enforce sanctions and embargo on the troubled
country to try to dislodge the junta.
</P>
<P>
"The embargo is already in force," said Malu, adding that
ECOMOG will ensure the agreement will not be violated.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that two container ships tried to berth at the
port in Freetown this morning, inviting shells fired by ECOMOG
troops in an unsuccessful attempt to deter them from coming to
port and unloading rice and other foodstuffs.
</P>
<P>
The shells went astray and killed a number of civilians, a
report said.
</P>
<P>
At three of the waterside areas hit, dead animals, rubble from
struck houses and utensils littered the ground, it said.
</P>
<P>
But Malu refuted the report, saying: "We can employ any means
to enforce the embargo. But it's particular for the junta to say
that we are bombarding and missing the target."
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, a spokesman of the junta said the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) did not have the right
to declare sanctions and embargo on the country.
</P>
<P>
"The only body that is responsible to establish sanctions is
the United Nations Security Council. What the ECOWAS has to do is
to make recommendations," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"The UN has not met. Nothing has been established. And it is
the responsibility of the government, which is a responsible
government, to take care of life and property," he added.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that junta reacted to the resolution
passed at the 20th ECOWAS summit last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, people in Freetown are reportedly marching to the
national stadium to mourn the dead in the bombardment.
</P>
<P>
The junta spokesman said they carried about 20 corps for the
funeral and one of the bodies was put in front of the United
Nations building.
</P>
<P>
According to a BBC report, the reported shelling by ECOMOG
troops prompted a demonstration of civilians in support of the
junta.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators appealed to the international community and
the United Nations to help put a stop to what they called
"Nigerians are kept to make Sierra Leone a puppet state".
</P>
</TEXT>
