<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BBC World's Coverage Of Diana's Funeral Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- BBC World, the BBC's 24-hour
news and information channel, will bring live and complete
coverage of the funeral of Diana, Princess of Wales, Saturday to
viewers all over the world.
</P>
<P>
Announcing in a press release, BBC World said today that the
audience in over 180 countries and territories will join with the
BBC's millions of viewers across the United Kingdom for live
coverage of the service in Westminster Abbey at the heart of
London.
</P>
<P>
The BBC's cameras will also follow the funeral procession
through the streets of London from St James' Palace, where the
Princess' body has lain in the Royal Chapel since being returned
from Paris Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The processional route of the Princess's coffin to her funeral
in Westminster Abbey is to be extended after the personal
intervention of the Prince of Wales.
</P>
<P>
It was reported the Prince feared that the many thousands
expected to pour into London Saturday would be denied access to
what promises to be an unprecedented show of national emotion.
</P>
<P>
A minute's silence will be observed following the funeral.
Then, viewers will see the procession travel from Westminster
Abbey to a tiny village church close to Diana's family home of
Althorp House, in the English countryside, for a private burial,
according to BBC World.
</P>
<P>
Commentary from Westminster Abbey will be provided by David
Dimbleby, one of Britain's foremost broadcasters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
