<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Create Viruses Against AIDS Virus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The first virus-killing
viruses that can enter AIDS-infected cells and destroy them have
been created by scientists, according to the U.S. medical
journal of Cell.
</P>
<P>
The approach, which works well in the test tube but has not
been tried yet in people or even animals, is to fight infection
with infection, said reports in the journal, which is to be
published Friday.
</P>
<P>
The newly created viruses target only cells that have already
been captured by HIV or the AIDS virus, the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
"It's absolutely amazing that you can make a virus that will
specifically target HIV-infected cells," said Ronald Desrosiers of
the New England Regional Primate Center, who plans to begin
testing one of the viruses soon on monkeys.
</P>
<P>
One version of the virus, created by Dr. John K. Rose and his
research team at Yale Medical School, is a genetically altered
form of vesicular stomatitis virus, or VSV, a bug that ordinarily
infects livestock.
</P>
<P>
Another is based on the rabies virus and was created by a team
led by Dr. Karl-Klaus Conzelmann of the Federal Research Center
for Virus Diseases of Animals in Tubingen, Germany.
</P>
<P>
"It's a completely new approach to limiting viral infection,"
Rose said. "This is the first virus that's an anti-virus."
</P>
<P>
Dr. Garry Nolan of Stanford University called the success
"highly significant" and "a leap forward" in the fight against
AIDS disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
