<HEADLINE> Albright Mideast Trip Unchanged Despite Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said
today that Secretary of State Madeleine Albright would go to the
Middle East next week as originally scheduled despite a bombing at
a downtown Jerusalem shopping mall this morning, killing at least
eight people and injuring more than 150.
</P>
<P>
"It's all the more important for Secretary Albright to go. It's
important she go right on out there, and we keep pushing this
thing," Clinton said at his vacation resort in Martha's Vineyard,
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
He said the bombings added a new sense of urgency to Albright's
diplomatic mission. A dangerous "limbo" could set in to the Middle
East peace process if "the enemies of peace" forced Albright to
postpone her trip, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Everything possible must be done to stop them (terrorist
bombings). The peace process can only move forward in a secure
environment," he said at a hastily arranged news conference. "This
is a message that Secretary Albright will emphasize when she
travels to the region next week."
</P>
<P>
Albright, who is in her Czech birthplace this week for her
vacation, issued a brief statement through the American embassy in
Prague shortly after the Jerusalem bombings, saying she would
"travel to the Middle East as scheduled."
</P>
<P>
"Fighting terror is a 24-hour-a-day job. Security cooperation
must be accompanied by unilateral Palestinian action to preempt
terror, destroy infrastructure as well as to create a political
climate where there is no tolerance for terror."
</P>
<P>
After the Jerusalem bombings this morning, Israel's Ambassador
Eliahu Ben-Elissar called on U.S. mediator Dennis Ross at the
State Department and conveyed a message from Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, saying that Israel's official
position was to welcome the secretary of state to travel to visit
the Jewish state "according to the original schedule." 
</P>
</TEXT>
