<HEADLINE> Miami Referendum to Decide on Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Officials are projecting a
voter turnout of 20 percent in the Miami referendum on whether to
abolish the city's government and turn it over to Dade County.
</P>
<P>
Officials say the turnout in Hispanic precincts could be as
high as 35 percent. Most of the city's Latins are expected to
oppose the measure, which reached the ballot as the result of last
fall's city hall scandals.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Joe Carollo predicted the voters would decide to keep
Miami's city government by a 70-30 margin, The United Press
International reported.
</P>
<P>
The measure was placed on the ballot by petition after federal
prosecutors indicted ranking city officials on various corruption
charges.
</P>
<P>
Also on the ballot today is a measure to create a strong mayor
and elect commissioners by district rather than at large. Both are
expected to pass. 
</P>
