<HEADLINE> EU Finance Ministers Urged to Quash Talk of Euro Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)'s
finance ministers were today urged to kill talk of delaying the
euro by adopting a firm commitment to the single currency
timetable at their meeting in Mondorf, Luxembourg, next week.
</P>
<P>
The call came from the chairwoman of the European Parliament's
monetary subcommittee, Christa Randzio-Plath, after declarations
by Bundesbank President Hans Tietmeyer and Italian Foreign
Minister Lamberto Dini gave rise to speculation that governments
might be developing postponement as a fallback position.
</P>
<P>
"We need a really clear message from ministers that the
timetable for the euro will be fully respected," Ms. Randzio-Plath
said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Talk of delaying the euro is damaging Europe's best interests.
Ministers must put an end to it," she added.
</P>
<P>
Ms Randzio-Plath, whose committee later today met Henri
Emmanuelli, president of the French National Assembly's finance
committee, congratulated the French government on ensuring that
action on job creation would be linked to the introduction of the
euro.
</P>
<P>
She urged ministers to improve the prospects of effective EU
action to overcome the problem of 18 million unemployed people by
adopting a pact on economic coordination. 
</P>
