<HEADLINE> Most Europeans Focus Attention on Unemployment: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Nearly nine out of 10
Europeans believe that it is necessary to have a common approach
to reducing unemployment in order to build Europe further, said a
survey published here today.
</P>
<P>
More than half of Europeans now feel better informed about the
European Union (EU) than they did two years ago. Only 14 percent
now feel less well informed, according to a survey conducted by
the EU's executive body, the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that 53 percent of Europeans feel that
it has become easier to get information about the EU during the
past two years. One fifth of those polled say that it has become
more difficult.
</P>
<P>
In the month after the Amsterdam Council, awareness of the
Intergovernmental Conference increased to 44 percent while nearly
seven in 10 Europeans had heard of the Amsterdam Council.
</P>
<P>
Support for national referenda dropped from 63 percent to 56
percent following the Amsterdam Council, an indication that people
are generally satisfied with the agreements reached during the
council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
