<HEADLINE> More Nepalese Can Drink Clean Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Ninety-three drinking water
projects have been constructed in the eastern development region
of Nepal in the past four fiscal years, benefiting about 400,000
people, the official RSS news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Development Bank (ADB) bore the lion's share of the
total cost of 287.44 million rupees (5.04 million U.S. dollars)
with loan assistance, while the rest were covered by the
government of Nepal and local people.
</P>
<P>
Another 26 drinking water projects which have been completed
under the third-phase program of the ADB have yet to be handed
over to the users, the RSS said.
</P>
<P>
And construction of 87 new drinking water projects in this
region under the ADB's fourth-phase drinking water program has
been proposed.
</P>
<P>
Once completed, these projects will bring pure drinking water
to an additional 105,000 people, the agency added.
</P>
<P>
Lack of clean drinking water is one of the biggest problems
facing the Nepalese.  
</P>
</TEXT>
