<HEADLINE> Policy On Dalai Lama Remains Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- China's central government will
welcome the Dalai Lama back to Tibet if he completely renounces
the idea of "independence of Tibet", Gyam Co, vice chairman of the
Tibetan Autonomous Regional Government, told a group of
Beijing-based foreign journalists today
</P>
<P>
"The central government's attitude towards the Dalai Lama
remains unchanged," he said, and the Dalai's "a high degree of
autonomy for Tibet" and "one country, two systems" ideas are
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that "one country, two systems" is a concept put
forth by Deng Xiaoping, which was meant to solve the Hong Kong,
Macao and Taiwan questions. It is only suitable for these three
issues, he said, and the resumption of feudal serfdom in Tibet
would only be a disaster for the Tibetan people.
</P>
<P>
To ensure that religious activities are conducted in an orderly
fashion, the vice chairman noted, the regional government started
patriotic education among the monks and nuns in the region last
year, increasing their awareness of the motherland, the law, and
Tibet's history.
</P>
<P>
"The vast majority of the monks and nuns understand and uphold
government policies and laws," he said. There are more than 1,700
temples and monastries, and 46,000 monks and nuns in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Since the establishment of the Tibet Autonomous Region in 1965,
it has had great changes. Last year, its GDP was as six times that of
1965 and average life expectancy jumped from 36 in 1951 to 65.
</P>
<P>
The vice chairman welcomed the visits of foreign journalists to
Tibet. "Objective and truthful coverage of Tibet will benefit our
work," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
