<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Praises Russian Position on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus today welcomed a Russian
official spokesman's statements on Moscow's position on the Cyprus
issue and its commitment to a controversial missile deal with
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, Government Spokesman
Manolis Christofides was making comments on statements by Russian
Foreign Ministry Spokesman Guennadi Tarasov on Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Russia's position stated by Tarasov to recognize only the
Republic of Cyprus and its lawful government corresponds with
U.N. resolutions, said Christofides.
</P>
<P>
Tarasov was quoted as telling Turkish journalists in Moscow
recently that there is only one internationally-recognized state
in Cyprus, and that no other country except Turkey recognizes the
illegal entity set up in the northern island.
</P>
<P>
The eastern Mediterranean island has remained divided since
1974 when Turkish troops invaded and took the norther third of the
island after a short-lived coup by some Greek Cypriots seeking
union with Greece. A break-away republic was unilaterally
established by Turkish Cypriots in the north in 1985.
</P>
<P>
The Russian official also called on the Greek and Turkish
Cypriot sides to step up efforts for a Cyprus settlement.
</P>
<P>
Christofides said "we endorse the plea for the intensification
of efforts toward achieving a true and permanent solution of the
Cyprus problem through honorable and constructive dialog for the
future of Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
According to Cyprus News Agency today, the Russian Foreign
Ministry spokesman also slammed Turkey over the issue of ship
searching.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Turkey has recently searched ships
passing through the Bosporus Strait in the Black Sea, suspecting
they carry parts of Russian S-300 anti-aircraft missiles bound for
Cyprus under a deal reached early this year.
</P>
<P>
Tarasov said the search of commercial ships by Turkey runs
contrary to the provisions of the 1936 Montreux Convention for
free crossing.
</P>
<P>
The issue will be discussed by the Russian and Turkish foreign
ministries, he added.
</P>
<P>
Tarasov pledged the missiles would be delivered according to
the agreed contract and there are no reasons for their delay.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus' decision to purchase Russian missiles has
triggered warning from Turkey that it will launch pre-emptive
strike against Cyprus if the missiles are deployed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
