The president said she decided to dissolve the Serbian
parliament and hold parliamentary elections in advance because
only in this way could the government be reshuffled.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic called for "comprehensive
elections" in Bosnia to solve its current crisis when meeting
Wednesday with Carlos Westerndorp, the international high
representative in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
"Comprehensive elections" mean the holding of presidential,
parliamentary and local elections simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
However, the government and parliament of the Bosnian Serb
republic, believed to be actually controlled by former president
Radovan Karadzic, have already decided to boycott Plavsic's
proposal for a new parliamentary election, and the local elections
scheduled for September 13-14 nationwide sponsored by the
international community.
</P>
<P>
The crisis within the Bosnian Serb leadership began in early
July.
</P>
<P>
Plavsic dissolved the parliament on July 3, but the decision
met strong opposition from the parliament and the Serb government.
</P>
<P>
The Constitutional Court in August ruled Plavsic's decision
unconstitutional and invalid. Plavsic rejected the verdict of the
court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
