<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Deputy Premier Calls for Corporate Self-Rescue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 5 (Xinhua) -- South Korean Deputy Prime
Minister Kang Kyung-shik today criticized the country's
economically troubled companies for depending on the government to
save them and urged them to rescue themselves.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Inha University in Inchon, Kang, the country's top
economic policymaker, blamed the country's trouble-stricken
economy on the mismanagement of banks and firms.
</P>
<P>
He criticized banks for indiscriminately extending loans to
large conglomerates on the brink of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
He said private companies should salvage themselves by
correcting their managerial mistakes rather than turning to the
government for help.
</P>
<P>
Kang rejected criticism that the government's latest aid
package, extended to some ailing local industrial and financial
firms, like the Kia Group and Korea First Bank, was not sufficient.
</P>
<P>
The government would no longer extend special aid or favors to
private enterprises mired in financial troubles, he said.
</P>
<P>
Excessive aid from the government would deteriorate economic
vitality, make corporate self-rescue efforts meaningless, and
increase the financial burden on ordinary citizens by driving up
the inflation rate, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
