<HEADLINE> South Korean Opposition Leader Proposes Delaying Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 5 (Xinhua) -- South Korean opposition leader
Kim Jong-pil today proposed delaying the presidential election,
due on December 18, to gain time to revise the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
"We still have time to amend the Constitution before President
Kim's term in office ends (in February next year) if he is
determined to do so," said Kim, leader and also presidential
candidate of the number two opposition party, United Liberal
Democrats (ULD).
</P>
<P>
Kim called for a national referendum on constitutional revision
aimed at building a parliamentary system of government.
</P>
<P>
The ULD leader said: "I have conveyed my intentions to
President Kim (Young-sam) several times. And I believe he has no
option other than accepting a parliamentary system if he wishes to
create a new political structure."
</P>
<P>
By law, Kim Jong-pil said, a presidential election can be held
up to 40 days before the presidential term of office expires, so
the coming presidential poll could be delayed until early January.
</P>
<P>
Kim Jong-pil's proposal came at a time when the ruling New
Korea Party (NKP) is in trouble over its presidential candidate
Lee Hoi-chang's fading popularity.
</P>
<P>
The ULD leader's proposal embarrassed the main opposition
National Congress for New Politics (NCNP), which is currently
negotiating with the ULD on putting forward a joint presidential
candidate.
</P>
<P>
The two parties have agreed to produce a compromise on the
joint candidacy by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
The NCNP withheld any immediate response to Kim's suggestions,
but some party officials expressed negative reactions.
</P>
<P>
"We need time before we react to his proposal," said Han
Kwang-ok, a NCNP vice president and top negotiator on the single
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
The splinter opposition Democratic Party (DP) immediately
brushed Kim's idea aside.
</P>
<P>
"Talking about a change of government system and election
delays when the country is experiencing a difficult period will
not help overcome the crisis," DP leader Cho Soon said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
