<HEADLINE> Philippine President May Opt to Run for Re-election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos said here today that he may opt to run for re-election
should the country's Constitution be amended to lift term limits.
</P>
<P>
"I must keep options open because it is not only my personal
future that is at stake here. It is the national interest and the
people's well-being", he said in his dialogue with businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said he was not worried about being criticized for his
new position, which is a departure from his repeated answer that
he will step down on June 30 next year as provided by the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
"If I must remain that way and get all kinds of flak, I'm
willing to go through that flak. I'm used to it. It is the bread
and butter of this office and during my entire 45 years in the
bureaucracy before becoming President. I'm used to this kind of
crisis situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Some representatives of the business community wrote to Ramos
on Monday, recommending the Ramos administration to focus on the
economic growth instead of the Charter change to lift term limits.
</P>
<P>
The country's economic growth rate slowed down to 5.9 percent
in the first half of the year compared with the 7.5 percent in the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The business group partially attributed the economic slowdown
and recent sharp plunge of the peso to the political uncertainty
arising from the Charter change move in the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, former President Corazon Aquino and Cardinal Jaime
Sin called for a rally on September 21 to protest against the
Charter change move that may bring in another dictator like
Ferdinand Marcos.
</P>
<P>
Ramos lashed back at the business group and the Catholic
Church, saying that they are instigating a "hate campaign" against
the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
