<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Banks Urged to Submit Foreign Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Philippine monetary authorities
is requiring all banks, including their subsidiaries and
affiliates, to report their daily foreign exchange positions
starting from September 10.
</P>
<P>
In a circular issued today, Central Bank Governor Gabriel
Singson ordered the banks to follow foreign exchange rules and
regulations, requiring bank officials to issue a monthly
certification to confirm that the reporting of the positions is
accurate.
</P>
<P>
Singson said what the banks are required to report includes
foreign currency positions against the peso at any branches and
offices, subsidiaries and affiliates both here and abroad.
</P>
<P>
The circular also applies to other entities engaged in foreign
exchange trading or foreign exchange corporations that are
affiliated with the banks either by ownership, management control
or influence, he said.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the Central Bank found out that some banks fueled the
peso's depreciation by buying more dollars at higher foreign
exchange rate than what was allowed by the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts considered the Central Bank's action a new move
to arrest the further decline of the peso, of which the value has
fallen by 23 percent since it was floated in a wider band on July
11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
