<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Under a grey autumn sky,
Japan's Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, dressed in somber
clothing, paid tribute to Chinese martyrs today at the Monument to
the People's Heros in Beijing's Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
At 2:30 this afternoon, a slight breeze ruffled the white
ribbons on a wreath for the monument. A military band played the
national anthems of China and Japan. An 18-member honor guard of
the PLA was present.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, accompanied by his wife and Minister of Finance Liu
Zhongli, chairman of the Reception Committee of the Chinese
Government, laid the wreath at the base of the monument,
straightened the ribbons, and bowed deeply to the monument, as the
band played soluting tune.
</P>
<P>
As the last notes of the music died out, the Hashimotos walked
around the monument slowly as their hosts described the meaning of
the relief carving around the monument.
</P>
<P>
At 2:45, Hashimoto and his entourage went into the Great Hall
of the People on the west side of the square to meet with the
Chinese leaders. 
