<HEADLINE> German Opposition Blocks Tax Reforms Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Germany's main opposition party,
the Social Democrats (SPD), today used its majority in the upper
house of parliament to veto again a tax reform package proposed by
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's centre-right government.
</P>
<P>
The bill before the Bundesrat was to introduce a tax reduction
of about 30 billion marks (16.6 billion U.S. dollars) from
1999. The SPD opposes the size of the tax cuts, saying they would
pose financial ruin for the public sector.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Theo Waigel had urged the Bundesrat to approve
the tax reform. He said it was urgently needed to help revive the
country's depressed economy and create more jobs.
</P>
<P>
Even international organizations were pressing Bonn to carry
out the reform, he added.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which had been adjusted after it was first blocked by
the SPD, will go back to mediation between the Bundesrat and the
Bundestag, the lower house, where the ruling coalition holds the
majority. 
</P>
