<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Faction Leader Returns to Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Faction leader, Mr Ali
Mahdi Mohamed, has today arrived in Mogadishu after a month long
absence in the Ethiopian capital of Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
Mr Ali Mahdi who was welcomed by cheering crowds was escorted
by dozens of technical vehicles belonging to his faction from the
dusty airstrip of Issaley, 15 km north of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Speaking with his supporters and reporters at his residence in
north Mogadishu, Mr Ali Mahdi said that the international
community has now fully realized what the Somali people need more
than anything else which is the formation of a representative
government before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Mr Ali Mahdi said the Somali factions who formed the National
Salvation Council (NSC) in Ethiopia are determined to form a
broad-based and strong government as he put it. Speaking about
the reconciliation process, Mr Ali Mahdi has called the Somali
people to reconcile within themselves and show a feeling of
forgiveness to each other.
</P>
<P>
Mr Ali Mahdi was leading a seven member delegation from the
National Salvation Council formed in Ethiopia by 26 factions
earlier this year. Mr Ali Mahdi has also been welcomed by his
factional police band who sang the national anthem of the country
and gave him a warm salutation at the airstrip.
</P>
<P>
Despite the hope for a government by the NSC factions soon,
the northeastern town of Bossaso where Ali Mahdi's dream
government would be established, has been having political
difficulties and tragedy ahead of its anticipated national
reconciliation conference due to be held in early November this
year.
</P>
<P>
A fire had devastated 250 huts and houses in the eastern
quarter of the town of Bossaso mainly inhabited by refugees six
days ago and displaced more than 700 people who lived in the
area. So it will be difficult for Bossaso to host more than 600
delegates from the multitude clans around the country for the
anticipated national reconciliation conference.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, there is a power struggle among the three separate
authorities in the northeastern region, the traditional elders,
the legislative council and the politicians of the Somali
Salvation Democratic Front (SSDF). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
