<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Concerned over Israeli Raid in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- France says it is "extremely
worried" by Israel's pre-dawn commando raid today in southern
Lebanon, in which at least 11 Israeli soldiers were killed.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said the clash
between Israeli troops and the Lebanese army and Shiite militiamen
was a "very grave incident".
</P>
<P>
Calling on all parties involved to exercise great restraint, he
said: "All should be done to ward off the risk of escalation in
order not to imperil the reconstruction of Lebanon and its unity,
and moreover, the peace process."
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Prime Minister Rafic Hariri told French President
Jacques Chirac earlier today by telephone that an airborne Israeli
commando group landed in a residential and tourist area at least
30 kilometers north of the habitual combat zone.
</P>
<P>
Hariri said Lebanon considered this raid a violation of the
Israeli-Lebanese truce agreement signed in April 1996 under the
mediation of the United States and France. It required both sides
of the conflict to spare civilians.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli soldiers immediately came under heavy fire from
Lebanese troops, Amal militiamen and Hezbollah, according to the
Israeli army.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu today described the
failed commando raid as "one of the worst tragedies" of the
Israeli army.
</P>
<P>
The raid came just one day after a triple suicide bombing by
suspected Palestinian militants killed seven and injured 170
others in a popular mall in the Jewish part of Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
