<HEADLINE> South Korea, Japan to Hold Fishery Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 5 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and Japan will hold
the fifth round of fishery talks here Wednesday to discuss
revision to the bilateral fishery agreement, Foreign Ministry
spokesman Lee Kyu-hyung said today.
</P>
<P>
The talks will be preceded by a one-day meeting Tuesday to look
into the alleged beating of a South Korean fisherman by Japanese
maritime security officers, he said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides started negotiations in May, 1996, on revising
the bilateral fishery accord, reached in 1965. But overlapping
claims to rocky islets in the waters between them have prevented
notable progress so far.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations stalled following Japan's seizure of South
Korean fishing boats in June and July in its newly expanded
territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
The talks were only resumed in Tokyo in August after the
foreign ministers of the two countries agreed on a set of meetings
to ease the dispute over the captures.
</P>
<P>
During the August talks, South Korean delegates agreed to
consider a provisional fishery agreement with Japan.
</P>
<P>
But they said consideration of this would be made on condition
South Korea's claim to the Tokto islets (Takeshima islets in
Japanese) were not affected and existing rights for South Korean
fishermen were fully guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
Japan has demanded an early solution to the fishing disputes by
means of a provisional agreement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
