<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets With Japanese PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- In a meeting with Japanese
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto today in Beijing's Great Hall of
the People, Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji said he hopes China and Japan
will maintain peace and friendship and work together to greet the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister's China trip is significant in this 25th
anniversary year of normalization of bilateral relations, Zhu
said, wishing the visit a complete success.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said that China has scored admirable achievements in
economic construction, reforms and opening up, and that its
economic development is important for maintaining regional and
global peace and stability, and means bright prospects for
Sino-foreign economic ties and trade. Japan wants to expand its
economic cooperation and trade with China and to help China in the
modernization drive, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu pointed out that great progress has been made in bilateral
relations since the normalization of bilateral relations 25 years
ago, but that there are still issues that can not be neglected. Of
these, the issue of history and the issue of Taiwan are the
most sensitive, and should be handled cautiously since they are
directly related to the political principles of Sino-Japanese
relations.
</P>
<P>
In the future, Zhu said, the two sides should continue to
strictly observe various principles of the Sino-Japanese Joint
Statement and the Sino-Japanese Treaty of Peace and
Friendship. The two countries have become each other's important
economic and trade partner, he noted, thanks to long-standing
efforts.
</P>
<P>
That good economic co-operation and trade have become an
important symbol for the sound development of bilateral relations,
he added. Last year two-way trade exceeded 60 billion U.S. dollars
and Japan has been China's biggest trade partner for 4 years in a
row, and that trade has maintained its momentum.
</P>
<P>
China's and Japan's economies have their strong and weak point,
but as long as the governments of the two countries actively
support and guide their economic ties in terms of policy, there is
great potential for co-operation, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the meeting were Minister of Finance Liu
Zhongli, the chairman of the Chinese government reception
committee, and Vice-foreign minister Tang Jiaxuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
