<HEADLINE> SADC Calls Upon International Community to Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) has called upon the international
community to help eradicate a contagious cattle disease which
threats the region, according to Zambia News Agency (ZANA) report
today.
</P>
<P>
Kaire Mbuende, executive secretary of the SADC Council of
Ministers, told a news briefing last evening in Malawi's southern
city Blantyre that the SADC council has decided to launch an
international appeal to help the region eradicate the disease.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that a contagious cattle lung disease
called Bovine Pleuropneaumonia (CBP) has spread in Botswana,
Angola, Zambia, Tanzania and Namibia.
</P>
<P>
The disease was first reported in Botswana where it has
claimed hundreds of thousands of cattle.
</P>
<P>
Mbuende added that the SADC Council of Ministers, which is
having a meeting in Blantyre in preparations for the upcoming
SADC summit schedualed for Monday, has urged the animal disease
control sector and the SADC Secretariate to liaise closely in
dealing with the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
At its opening meeting Thursday, the SADC council expressed
its deep concern over the continued epidemic outbreak of the
cattle disease, saying that it has reached "crisis proportions"
and is a serious economic threat to the region which relies
heavily on livestock farming.
</P>
<P>
The council also commended the Botswana government for its
efforts to eradicate the disease and noted that restocking was
under way in a district where over 300,000 cattle were destroyed
in the process of eradicating CBP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
