<HEADLINE> Dialogue Enhances Sino-Japanese Trust: Hashimoto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto said here today Japan should correctly view its
history, face the future and forge a long-term good neighbor,
friendly and cooperative relationship with China.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered at the State Institute of Administration,
Hashimoto noted that the two countries previously passed through a
period of misery and that this is a fact.
</P>
<P>
He said that in a prime minister talk released in 1995, the
Japanese government made clear its understanding of the past
history.
</P>
<P>
He said that Japan will continue to proceed on the basis of the
talk to correctly view the past, increase its understanding of
history and carry out with China dialogue and cooperation that
will help create the future.
</P>
<P>
He said that he plans to visit the "September 18 Incident"
memorial in Shenyang in northeast China. The "September 18
Incident" marks the beginning of Japan's full-scale aggression
against China in 1931.
</P>
<P>
He said that the visit to the memorial is aimed to express his
personal feeling on viewing the past correctly.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto pointed out that Japan has been one of the major
beneficiaries of peace and development in the Asia-Pacific Region
and the world over the past decades.
</P>
<P>
He said that Japan has made a profound self-examination since
the end of World War II, and totally negated the path of becoming
a military power. Japan has instead set an objective of turning
itself into a peaceful country and achieved the monumental growth
it enjoys today.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Sino-Japanese relationship is of paramount
importance to Japan, and expressed the hope that his visit will
become a milestone in the development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto addressed the Taiwan issue by noting that the
Japanese government will adhere to the principles defined in the
Sino-Japanese Joint Statement and Sino-Japanese Treaty of
Friendship. He said Japan will never support "two Chinas" or
"Taiwan Independence". 
</P>
</TEXT>
