<HEADLINE> Chirac to Visit Mauritania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
left here today for a two-day state visit to Mauritania to ``mark
his attachment and that of France to the African continent,'' said
the Elysee presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
This visit is apparently aimed at boosting French-African
relations following a series of crisis taking place this year in
French-speaking African countries including former Zaire, the
Central African Republic and the Congo Republic.
</P>
<P>
Chirac will hold talks with Mauritanian President Maaouya Ould
Sidi Ahmed Taya in Nouakchott today on cooperation in water
resource development and agriculture, and is expected to announce a
number of aid projects by France in Mauritania, according to
presidential spokeswoman Catherine Colonna.
</P>
<P>
This is the fifth visit by Chirac to the African continent since
he became president in May 1995. He is also the third French
president to visit Mauritania, after President Georges Pompidou in
1978 and President Francois Mitterrand in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Chirac is accompanied by Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine, and
former Prime Minister Pierre Messmer, who was governor of Atar
during the French colonial rule. 
</P>
