<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expands Construction of State Information Projects (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has
initiated a series of national information projects in recent
years in an effort to keep abreast of stunning developments in
the world information industry, according to a high-ranking
official with the Ministry of Electronics Industry (MEI).
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with Xinhua, MEI Minister Hu Qili said
that related projects, dubbed "golden projects", cover almost all
major fields in the Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
According to Hu, the "Golden Bridge" project has led to the
establishment of a nationwide public economic information network
linking 24 major Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
Trial operations of the "Golden Card" project, an electronic
currency system, are under way in 12 provinces, with six provinces
currently handling partial interbank financial transactions.
</P>
<P>
Tax departments in 350 cities have introduced the "Golden Tax"
project this year.
</P>
<P>
China has used its information infrastructure to launch a
number of large-scale application systems related to
macro-economic control, electronic data intercharge (EDI), airline
bookings, railway and electricity dispatching, public security and
office automation.
</P>
<P>
Hu said the development of information technology (IT) will be
a vital index for measuring a country's comprehensive strength in the
coming century. "China has a large developing economy which offers
a vast market for the IT industry," said Hu.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate that the market scale of China's electronics
and information industry will top one trillion yuan by the year
2000. They also note that the figure will quite likely hit six
trillion yuan in 2010 and in so doing will transform China -- the
world's largest IT market which will offer "a large pie for all
capable participants in the field", according to the minister
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expands Construction of State Information Projects (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hu said China has closely followed trends in worldwide
networking in pursuit of opportunities to promote the nation's
development. MEI has proceeded under the leadership of the State
Council, China's highest administrative body, and has tried hard
to organize and coordinate the undertaking of key IT
projects. "MEI's efforts to promoted the development and
applications of computers have paid off," said Hu.
</P>
<P>
"It is imperative for local companies to develop and file
information that will crystalize the Chinese culture and
achievements in the moderization drive," according to Hu.
</P>
<P>
He urged local enterprises to further expand their
understanding of the role networking will play in future market
competition. "They should introduce their own home pages on the
Internet in order to protect their invisible property and polish
their market image," said Hu.
</P>
<P>
MEI statistics show that China's electronics and information
industry has registered sustained, rapid and healthy growth since
1992, with total output hitting 300 billion yuan in 1996,
quadruple the 1992 figure.
</P>
<P>
China's electronics and information industry maintained 25
percent annual growth in terms of industrial output, sales and
profits and taxes between 1992-1996. "The industry has been
transformed from a predominantly manufacturing sector into an
industry which combines hardware production with software
development and application services," said Hu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
