<HEADLINE> SADC Brings More Private Involvement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE, MALAWI, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) has been bringing more private
involvement in the economic development, a SADC principal
economist said here today.
</P>
<P>
Chungu Mwila told a news briefing that the private sector has
been involved in 384 projects with an estimated C\tx9R]pDZe5$[aIVYsQ\oIWZo9R
e followed by energy and mining
sectors,sid.
</P>
<P>
When the Southern African Development Coordination Conference
(SADCC) was established in early 1980s, it was largely an
inter-governmental political organization, but since it was
turned into the SADC in 1992 it has gradually shifted its focus
on economic development and has made attempts to bring private
sectors together.
</P>
<P>
Private sectors are represented in the delegations to attend
the summit meeting, he said.
</P>
<P>
SADC set up a business council in 1991 and the council has
achieved a lot in bringing more private involvment in economic
activities in the past few years, he said.
</P>
<P>
To encourage private involvment is also to make the economies
self-sufficient by mobilizing their own resources.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, SADC set up power pool to bring their own resources
of the member countries togather and utilize them, he said.
</P>
<P>
The power pool also cooperates with non-members like Zaire
(now the Democratic Republic of Congo), the economist said.
</P>
<P>
A report on the private involvement will be presented to the
SADC summit to be held here next Monday, Mwila said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
