<BODY>
<HEADLINE> LDP Regains Majority in Japan's Lower House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Japan's ruling Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) regained sole control of the House of
Representatives (Lower House) today for the first time in four
years after it accepted a former member back into its fold.
</P>
<P>
Naoto Kitamura, a Lower House member who left the opposition
New Frontier Party (NFP) in May, applied to rejoin the LDP today
and was immediately approved by the LDP's Party Ethics Committee.
</P>
<P>
The LDP now holds 250 seats in the 500-seat Lower House,
regaining the majority it lost in the 1993 general elections.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, LDP lost its majority for the first time since its
1955 formation when a group of LDP members, including Kitamura,
broke away from the party. The LDP was an opposition party at
that time when a coalition government led by then Japan New Party
chief Morihiro Hosokawa was formed.
</P>
<P>
The LDP, the leading party in a coalition with two noncabinet
allies, the Social Democratic Party (SDP) and New Party Sakigake,
eventually regained the premiership in January 1996 with LDP
president Ryutaro Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Chief Cabinet Secretary Seiroku
Kajiyama said that the LDP and its two parliamentary partners will
remain despite the LDP's recovery of a simple majority in the
Lower House.
</P>
<P>
The top government spokesman said the government will continue
to seek policy-by-policy coopration with opposition parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
