<HEADLINE> Foreign Banks Contribute More to GDP in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The foreign banks in Bangladesh,
with only about 7 percent share of the local market, have put in a
stunning 70 percent of the banking sector's total contribution to
the country's gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
During the last fiscal year (July 1, 1995 - June 30, 1996) the
contribution of the banking sector to the GDP of 33 billion U.S.
dollars was estimated at 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Operational efficiency, cautious lending approach and prudent
management of funds were attributed to the higher contribution by
the 14 foreign banks which also managed to maintain a steady rise
in their market share although they are small in size, the
Financial Express reported today.
</P>
<P>
The share of foreign banks in the banking sector's total
deposits rose to 7.25 percent in 1997 from 4.65 percent in 1994
while the share of lending jumped to 6.5 percent from 4.35 percent
during the period, the paper quoted bank sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Other profitability ratios, such as return on assets, return on
equity and the net interest margin of the foreign banks reached
4.75 and 6 percent respectively, which the sources said were quite
impressive.
</P>
<P>
Of the total lending by the foreign banks, 36 percent has been
to the trade sector, 28 percent to the manufacturing sector as
long-term loans, 19 percent to industries as working capital and
the remaining 17 percent to small borrowers under different
consumer credit schemes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
