<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chief Justice Lists Priorities for HKSAR Judiciary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Andrew Li, chief justice of
the Final Appeal Court of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR), today outlined the priorities for the HKSAR
judiciary, expressing determination to make the concept of "one
country, two systems" a success.
</P>
<P>
Speaking this afternoon at his first news conference since the
July 1 handover, Li said that as an institution of
the HKSAR government exercising judicial power, the judiciary is
an institution that belongs to the community and serves the
community.
</P>
<P>
"As chief justice, my mission is to lead the judiciary into the
21st century to maintain the rule of law so as to make the concept
of 'one country, two systems' a success," he said.
</P>
<P>
Li, who took office as chief justice of the Court of Final
Appeal on July 1, stressed that for the first time in its history
Hong Kong has its own final appellate court.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that his priorities in the next few years
include the following:
</P>
<P>
-- to work hard to ensure that the final court ranks among the
best of final courts in other common law jurisdictions;
</P>
<P>
-- to continue to make progress with the use of the Chinese
language in the courts and to ensure that the common law is
maintained and developed;
</P>
<P>
-- to strengthen judicial education and training for the
judges;
</P>
<P>
-- to ensure that the infrastructure (particularly staff)
support for the courts' functioning is efficient; and
</P>
<P>
-- to develop mutual understanding with the judicial colleagues
in the motherland and links with other common law jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
According to the Basic Law, the judicial system previously
practiced in Hong Kong shall be maintained except for those
changes consequent upon the establishment of the Court of Final
Appeal.
</P>
<P>
The power of final adjudication of the HKSAR shall be vested in
the Court of Final Appeal of the HKSAR, which may as required
invite judges from other common law jurisdictions to sit on the
Court of Final Appeal, the law stipulates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Strengthen Transport, Communication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) today decided to firm up the establishment
of an transport network that will link key Asian capitals and
boost regional transport and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In a joint press statement released at the end of the one-day
Third ASEAN Transport Ministers Meeting (ATM) in the southern
Philippine city of Cebu, transport ministers agreed to lay down
the foundation for a vast transport infrastructure plan among the
ASEAN countries.
</P>
<P>
Dubbed as "Vision 2020", the draft plan also highlights a
"partnership in dynamic development" which espouses closer
economic and social integration and strengthen peace, stability
and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, nine transport ministers and 200 delegates from
the ASEAN countries reviewed the progress made on the
implementation of the ASEAN Plan of Action in Transport and
Communications and other new initiatives adopted at the second ATM
in Chiang Mai, Thailand, in February 1997.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also agreed to finalize the draft Framework
Agreement on Multimodal Transport and Trade Facilitation
incorporating all inputs from all relevant governmental bodies and
private sectors.
</P>
<P>
They decided to formulate the ASEAN agreement on the mutual
recognition of commercial vehicle inspection certificates which
was suggested in a report submitted by the Fourth Senior Transport
Officials Meeting held in the same city on September 2-4.
</P>
<P>
The transport ministers agreed to hold the Fourth ASEAN
Transport Ministers Meeting in Singapore in September 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
