<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Seeks Declaration to Ban Land-Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE, MALAWI, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) is seeking to come up with a
declaration to ban land-mines in the region.
</P>
<P>
SADC executive secretary Kaire Mbuende said here on Thursday
that areas bordering Malawi and Mozambique are infested with
anti-personnel land-mines.
</P>
<P>
He said that SADC is one of the worst hit regions in the world
by land-mines, adding that there are more land-mines than people
in the region.
</P>
<P>
The SADC ministers' conference, which started on Thursday to
make preparations for the SADC summit to be held here next
Monday, also resolved that member states start preparations to
minimize the impact of the anticipated drought in the region to
be caused by El Nino climatic phenomenon from south east Pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
"The region had been critically hit by drought due to lack of
preparedness," Mbuende said.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting the minister also highlighted the SADC trade
protocol, an agreement to reduce and then remove trade tariffs
and create a free trade zone in the region as being the launching
pad for successful regional integration in southern Africa,
according to Mbuende.
</P>
<P>
But so far only four countries -- Mauritius, Malawi, Tanzania
and Zimbabwe -- have ratified the protocol.
</P>
<P>
The council meeting also adopted two protocols on mining and
education and training. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
