<HEADLINE> Safety Rules for HK's Overseas Tour Operators Proposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Some 3,000 Hong Kong guides
who conduct overseas tours will have to obtain professional
certificates under a proposal to improve safety, obviously in wake
of series of accidents involving Hong Kong residents.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's Travel Industry Council is expected to issue to its
1,200 member agents with rules on the safety of overseas tours and
the appointment of overseas partners, who must have adequate
insurance coverage, before next year.
</P>
<P>
Agents who fail to comply could have their licenses suspended,
local English-language newspaper South China Morning Post reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The proposals were among six recommendations endorsed Thursday
by the Travel Agents Advisory Committee.
</P>
<P>
A regular meeting was held after the Manila Bay accident last
month in which a boat capsized, drowning seven Hong Kong tourists.
</P>
<P>
The committee, comprising travel industry members and
government officials, agreed on the need to boost professionalism
among the 3,000 full and part-time guides, including those
conducting overseas tours.
</P>
<P>
It suggested training for outbound tour guides, including how
to handle emergencies, should be improved.
</P>
<P>
A certificate system should also be introduced, it said.
</P>
<P>
Committee member and provisional legislator Howard Young said:
"The idea of the certificate system is to assure the tour guides
possess all-round qualifications in the profession."
</P>
<P>
Their training could include safety knowledge, courtesy, and
how to protect tourists' interests, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
