<HEADLINE> Russian Government Denies Nuke Weapons Have Been Missing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Russian Defense Ministry today
denied former presidential adviser Alexander Lebed's remarks that
some of the country's suitcase-sized nuclear bombs were missing.
</P>
<P>
A ministry spokesman said there are no nuclear bombs in Russia
that are out of control of the Russian armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Lebed, former national security adviser to President Boris
Yeltsin, told CBS News, of the United States, that the Russian
military had lost track of over 100 suitcase-sized nuclear bombs.
</P>
<P>
In his response, the official spokesman, Vladimir Uvatenko,
said Lebed never dealt with nuclear security issues and was in no
way to have any knowledge in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Lebed's statement, Uvatenko said, "can cause nothing but a
smile."
</P>
<P>
It was impossible that the nuclear weapons would be stored
without being properly registered or had been used or destroyed
and not accounted for, he said.
</P>
<P>
Lebed said in the interview with the U.S. TV network that the
bombs, which can fit into a suitcase or backpack, can kill up to
100,000 people and devastate part of a city.
</P>
<P>
The former Yeltsin aide said he was not sure what had happened
to the missing bombs, but was certain they were not under the
control of the Russian military.
</P>
<P>
He speculated that the missing bombs could be in Georgia,
Ukraine, the Baltic nations or elsewhere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
