<HEADLINE> U.S. Aircraft Carrier Anchors at Japanese Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. aircraft carrier
"Independence" anchored at Otaru port on Japan's northernmost main
island of Hokkaido this morning, making it the first U.S. aircraft
carrier to dock at a civilian port in Japan, reports reaching here
said.
</P>
<P>
Naval authorities said the visit of the 80,643-ton carrier with
1,700 crewmen on board was aimed at strengthening friendly ties
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
However, the warship's arrival was met by some 2,300 people
from civic peace groups and labor unions who were protesting the
visit on grounds that the U.S. military was using the visit as a
test run for emergency situations covered by an ongoing review of
the Japan-U.S. Guidelines on Defence Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Residents marched through the streets of Otaru with banners
saying, "go home U.S. navy" after they learned that Otaru is a
candidate port for the U.S. military in the event of an emergency.
</P>
<P>
City officials said they received 533 requests from citizens
not to permit the visit by the Independence.
</P>
<P>
The Independence will leave Otaru, a popular tourist spot in
Hokkaido, on September 9. 
</P>
</TEXT>
