<HEADLINE> Sino-Japanese Scientific and Economic Symposium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and Japanese leaders
offered congratulation on today's opening of a symposium on
Sino-Japanese scientific, technological and economic exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng and Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto sent congratulatory letters noting that talks between
the two countries on cooperation and exchanges in all fields are
of great importance to promoting healthy Sino-Japanese relations
into the next century.
</P>
<P>
More than 180 scholars, businesspeople and representatives from
nongovernmental organizations in the two countries attended
today's symposium which was held to mark the 25th anniversary of
the normalization of Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
Participants discussed issues on the economy, culture,
education, and science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Xu Guanhua, vice-minister of the State Science and Technology
Commission, said that the two countries have witnessed remarkable
progress in promoting exchanges and cooperation in science and
technology. He also noted the bright future for expanded exchanges.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that the two countries face common tasks in
developing science and technology, with both having their own
advantages in the field, The cooperation will contribute greatly
to social and economic growth in the two countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
Xu expressed hope that Sino-Japanese scientific cooperation
will advance to a new level based on the highly-significant
symposium.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Guangzhao, chairman of the Chinese Association for Science
and Technology, and Beijing Vice-Mayor Hu Zhaoguang also attended
the symposium.  
</P>
