<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
closed stronger today in mixed trading, with optimistic economic
data and an influx of Asian investors lifting the local bourse.
</P>
<P>
Michael Baker, a broker with Henderson Charlton Jones, said he
was surprised at the strength of the Australian market, with its
performance underpinned by activity in Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
"Asian investors are coming into our market, treating it as a
safe haven from the volatile Asian markets," Baker said.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index closed 17.5 points higher at 2626.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 389.81 million shares worth 842.26
million Australian dollars (614.84 million U.S. dollars). Rises of
587 outnumbered falls of 469.
</P>
<P>
Junior explorer Jubilee Gold Mines was again heavily traded
after revealing further drilling results from its Cosmos nickel
find in the state of Western Australia yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Jubilee shares, which gained 59 cents yesterday, closed a
further 15.3 cents, or 11.86 percent higher, at 1.44 Australian
dollars with a turnover of 14.4 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Gold bullion in Sydney was trading lower at 321.15 U.S. dollars
an ounce from 322.45 dollars at yesterday's close.
</P>
<P>
The All Resources Index closed up 4.5 points at 1358.9 and the
All Industrials was 33.5 points up at 4247.4.
</P>
<P>
In the resource sector, market bellwether BHP gained 4 cents to
16.77 Australian dollars while mining giant WMC shed 7 cents to
6.87 Australian dollars on a turnover of 4.89 million shares and
Rio Tinto was down 2 cents at 19.85 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The four major banks in Australia all closed higher, with ANZ
18 cents stronger at 9.92 Australian dollars, National Australia
Bank rising 13 cents to 19.18 Australian dollars, Westpac 11 cents
firmer at 7.94 Australian dollars and the Commonwealth lifting 4
cents to 15.38 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Macquarie Bank closed 20 cents higher at 13.2 Australian
dollars and Adelaide Bank surged 22 cents to 5.16 Australian
dollars. 
