<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Business Resumes in Liberia's Seaports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Traffic is returning to the two
main seaports of Liberia following the end of its seven-year
civil war, the Daily Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the main international airport is preparing to
reopen within weeks.
</P>
<P>
Reopening the ports and Robertsfield International Airport
outside the capital Monrovia are key objectives of President
Charles Taylor, the former warlord who won the July elections
ending the war he launched in December 1989.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted officials at Monrovia Free Port as saying
that the number of ships calling there and the Buchanan Port to
the southeast had risen markedly since Taylor was inaugurated on
August 2.
</P>
<P>
Ships carrying logs and rubber and those bringing in vehicles
and goods are calling at the port of Monrovia and Buchanan daily,
an ports spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Some have had to wait for days while others are unloading.
This increase really took off after the inauguration of the
president, Sidiki Trawally added.
</P>
<P>
He said port workers had resumed night shifts due to growing
traffic at the Monrovia Port, built in 1948 by the United States.
</P>
<P>
But no detailed traffic data are available.
</P>
<P>
The two ports and minor ones at Harper and Greenville are key
to any moves to revive an economy based on rubber, iron ore and
timber before war devastated the country.
</P>
<P>
Shipping was suspended during the war, and activity at the
ports depended on the state of the conflict and remained under
the control of the west African peace-keeping force known as
ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, ECOMOG lifted a shipping embargo along Liberia's
coastal waters, saying the zone is now safe with the formal end
of the civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
