<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Rallies Support for S. Africa's Olympic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria may have agreed to
rally support for South Africa's bid to host the 2004 Olympic
Games, as a result of a deal between the two leading African
countries.
</P>
<P>
"This Day" newspaper reported today that, by the deal, Nigeria
will help rally other African countries behind South Africa so
that Africa will be hosting the games for the first time since
1896, when the modern Olympic games were born.
</P>
<P>
The International Olympic Committee will vote today in
Lausanne, Switzerland, to choose the host of the games from Cape
Town, Stockolm, Athens, Rome and Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
By their joint effort, Nigeria and South Africa will make sure
that all the 20 votes for Africa will go to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Of the 111 votes to be cast today, Europe has 38, Asia and
Oceania 19 and the Americans 34.
</P>
<P>
The deal between Nigeria and South African is believed to be
struck during Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi's visit to S.
Africa earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi delivered a special message from Nigerian head of state,
General Sani Abacha to President Nelson Mandela. He denied that
the two countries have problems, saying that the relations are
cordial.
</P>
<P>
According to This Day's report, in return for Nigeria's
support, South Africa has agreed not to oppose Nigeria "in any
way" at the October Commonwealth Summit in Edinburgh, Scotland,
which will take the final decision on Nigeria's membership.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has also agreed to cooperate with Nigeria-led
ECOWAS (the Economic Community of West African States) in its
effort to restore the legitimate government of President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah in Sierra Leone, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic relations between the two countries got sour in
1995, when South Africa led the campaign at the Auckland summit
that suspended Nigeria's Commonwealth membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
