<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Price Decline Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Last week's decline in wool
price was arrested during sales across three states in Australia
this week as the benchmark eastern market indicator climbed 17
Australian cents to 688 Australian cents (502 U.S. cents) a
kilogram.
</P>
<P>
An average increase in prices of between 2.5 and 3 percent at
sales in Sydney, Melbourne and Fremantle represented a welcome
turnaround in the market, the Australian Council of Wool Exporters
(ACWE) said.
</P>
<P>
"While the lower Australian dollar, a stronger European
presence and the level of Chinese inquiry, recent contractual
problems notwithstanding, help to explain market developments this
week, no-one in the trade has a clear or confident view of the
short-term outlook," the ACWE said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"At best exporters expect there will continue to be
fluctuations around 700 Australian cents (511 U.S. cents) a
kilogram clean benchmark as measured by Wool International's
eastern market indicators."
</P>
<P>
Sales will continue next week in the two coastal cities of
Sydney and Adelaide with 56,300 bales rostered for sale.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
