<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Four years after the signing of the Oslo peace agreements
between Israel and Palestinians, it is more and more difficult to
define the trail of the "peace process" which is dotted with the
bodies of the victims of blind attacks. The latest suicide attack
in Jerusalem is more aimed at U.S. President Bill Clinton than
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, as it is aimed at
rejecting the new turning for the peace process with the visit by
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to Israel next week.
</P>
<P>
-- Hocine Ait-Ahmed, the head of the opposition Front of
Socialist Forces of Algeria, Thursday made an appeal to the
Socialist governments of Britain and France to "make an emergency
initiative in favor of the peace in Algeria." He thus reinforced
the initiative opened last week by United Nations Secretary
General Kofi Annan who, to the annoyment of the Algerian
authorities, appealed for an end of escalation of violence in
Algeria.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a bombing attack killed two and injured three in
Algiers on Thursday in the commercial district of Bouzareah.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Household taxes in France will increase by several billion
francs next year, according to the preliminary outline of a draft
budget law for 1998. The measure, described as indispensable for
maintaining state income at a normal level, will follow a drastic
increase of corporate taxes on enterprise interests which was
decided in July by the Socialist government of Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin.
</P>
<P>
-- The French government wants to keep Christian Blanc in the
seat of the president of Air France, the national carrier of
France. After a meeting between Prime Minister Lionel Jospin and
Blanc Thursday, the prime minister's office said that the
government hopes that Blanc will continue his mission but stressed
that privatization of Air France, which is demanded by Blanc, is
"not on the agenda." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
