<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Open up New Prospect for China's Diplomacy in 1990s (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The third generation of the
collective leadership of the Communist Party of China (CPC) with
Jiang Zemin at the core, steadfastly carrying out the independent
foreign policy of peace devised by their predecessors, has opened
up new prospects for China's diplomacy in the 1990s, especially
since the 14th CPC National Congress five years ago.
</P>
<P>
The third generation of the CPC collective leadership,
adhering to Deng Xiaoping's penetrating analysis of the
international situation and his strategic guiding principles on
diplomacy, have fully demonstrated their outstanding ability to
deal with diplomatic and international affairs under the
complicated situation that emerged after the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
China's diplomacy has flourished in a very active and
successful period since the beginning of the 1990s, during which
the relations between China and other countries around the world
have been universally improved and developed, especially the
friendly ties between China and its neighbors and the other
developing countries, on the basis of the Five Principles of
Peaceful Co-existence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China has been unremitting in its opposition of
outside actions that violate its sovereignty and interfere in its
internal affairs, thereby effectively safeguarding its state
sovereignty and national dignity.
</P>
<P>
China's international status and its influence in international
affairs continue to improve and the country has forged diplomatic
relations with 160 countries throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
The world entered a period of transition from the old structure
to a new one after the Cold War. The third generation of the CPC
collective leadership, under the changing and severe international
situation, consistently abiding by the principles of "one focus"
of economic construction and "two basic points" of adherence to
the four cardinal principles and to the reform and opening up to
the outside world, and holding fast to the two major issues of
peace and development in today's world, has put forward and
implemented a series of principles and policies concerning
bilateral and multi-lateral relations, and has achieved remarkable
successes in diplomatic work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Open up New Prospect for China's Diplomacy in 1990s (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has also increased and consolidated the ties with its
neighbors and with developing countries since the beginning of the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
-- The relations between China and its neighbors and other
Asian countries have entered a new period of good-neighborly
cooperation since the 1990s. Major progress has been made by China
and its neighbors in settling issues left over from history,
demarcating boundary lines and in promoting economic and trade
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin's state visits to the
Philippines, India, Pakistan and Nepal have confirmed the
development direction of the relations between China and the four
countries in the next century. China and India signed an
important agreement on increasing mutual trust. President Jiang
also elaborated China's policy towards South Asia during his visit
to the region.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese leaders' visits to Vietnam, the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea, the Republic of Korea and ASEAN countries, along
with the fact that China became the full dialogue partner of the
ASEAN last year have elevated the relations between China and
those states to a new level.
</P>
<P>
-- Sino-Japanese ties have generally maintained a good
development momentum in recent years. China and Japan, two major
neighboring countries in east Asia, have scored progress in their
cooperation in every area. the year 1997 marks the 25th
anniversary of the normalization of Sino-Japanese relations, and
China hopes that Japan will acknowledge and properly approach the
historical issues, and abide by the basic principles guiding
Sino-Japanese ties to boost bilateral relations in a healthy,
stable and long-term fashion.
</P>
<P>
-- The relations between China and developing countries have
been constantly increased and strengthened. China, the world's
largest developing country, and the other developing countries
have always supported each other in international affairs and
their links have been expanded in every field on the basis of
equality and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
China put forward a five-point suggestion concerning
Sino-African relations and a five-point principle guiding
Sino-Latin American ties during Chinese President Jiang Zemin's
visit to Africa last year and during Premier Li Peng's visit to
Latin America, respectively, which promoted the political and
economic cooperation with the two continents and their common
development.
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Li Peng's visit to six African countries this year
not only has helped increase Sino-African traditional friendship,
but also has helped enhance the economic and trade collaboration
between the two sides under the current new situation.
</P>
<P>
-- China established diplomatic relations this year with the
Bahamas and St Lucia in Central America and the Cook Islands in
the South Pacific. South Africa also announced that it would forge
diplomatic ties with China by the end of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Open up New Prospect for China's Diplomacy in 1990s (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China and Russia have set up a strategic and cooperative
partnership oriented towards the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Since the normalization of the Sino-Russian relations in 1992,
the relations between the two countries have been developing
steadily and soundly. Russian President Boris Yeltsin's two trips
to China and Chinese President Jiang Zemin's visit to Russia last
April have helped push the bilateral relations to a new stage of
comprehensive and deepened development.
</P>
<P>
China and Russia, as big neighboring countries, have vowed to
set up a 21st century-oriented strategic and cooperative
partnership of equality and mutual trust, based on non-alignment,
non-confrontation and not targeting any third party. Such an
innovative relationship is conducive to maintaining regional and
global peace and security, conforms to the trend and needs of the
current world situation and the development of international
relations, while providing the necessary space for forming ideas
about relations between big countries under the new situation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on strengthening trust on military-occupied land
in border areas and the agreement on mutual reduction of military
forces in border areas signed by China, Russia and three Central
Asian countries have successfully solved the issue of the
stability and peace of the more than 7000-kilometer long border
areas.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Russia last April, President Jiang Zemin
and President Yeltsin also signed a joint statement on the world's
multi-polarization. The establishment of a new world order has made
contributions to promoting the process of global multi-polarization
and the establishment of new international political and economic
orders characterized by peace and stability, justice and reason.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Open up New Prospect for China's Diplomacy in 1990s (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has disregarded the so-called "sanctions" imposed by the
western countries and quashed the attempt to split and
westernize China by the international anti-China forces. The
relations between China and the western countries have been
gradually improved and developed.
</P>
<P>
-- Sino-European ties, especially China's ties with
Germany, France and other western European nations, are growing
continuously. During his visit to Germany in 1995, President Jiang
Zemin pointed out that mutual respect, seeking common ground while
preserving differences, equality and mutual benefit are the basic
principles guiding Sino-Western European relations.
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Li Peng, during the Asia-Europe Summit in March
1996, summarized five characteristics for the new partnership
between Asia and Europe: mutual respect and treating each other
equally; seeking common ground while preserving differences and
learning from each other; promoting mutual understanding and
establishing mutual trust; mutual benefit and mutual complement
with each other's strong points; keeping an eye to the future and
joint development. These principles have laid down a solid
foundation for the constant growth of Sino-European relations.
</P>
<P>
-- French President Jacque Chirac's successful visit to China
this year boosted Sino-French ties, especially bilateral economic
and trade relations.
</P>
<P>
-- Sino-US relations, after a period of twists and turns, have
headed in a positive direction toward improvement and development
since the second half of last year. This year there have been
continuous high-level contacts between the two countries. US
Vice-President Al Gore, Speaker of House of Representatives Newt
Gingrich, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and dozens of US
congress members visited China.
</P>
<P>
Also, the Chinese military fleet toured the US mainland for the
first time. President Jiang Zemin's upcoming state visit to the US
this fall will surely mark a milestone for the further advancement
of Sino-US relations.
</P>
<P>
The growth of Sino-US ties suffered a serious setback in 1995
when the US allowed Lee Teng-hui of Taiwan to visit it. During the
last four Sino-US summits, President Jiang pointed out that
handling Sino-US relations, both sides should abide by the basic
policy of "increasing mutual trust, reducing troubles, developing
cooperation and refraining from confrontation", and the two
presidents have reached consensus on the principle of developing
Sino-US ties.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang also proposed recently that Chinese and US
leaders should look at the overall situation of bilateral ties
from a strategic point of view, adhere to the principles of mutual
respect, non-interference in each other's internal affairs, and
consultations on an equal footing, try to "expand common
understranding, increase trust, reduce differences and jointly
build the future."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China adheres to the principles concerning the
issues of Taiwan, bilateral trade and human rights, having thus
safeguarded its sovereignty and dignity.
</P>
<P>
-- The smooth return of Hong Kong and the coming return of
Macao to the motherland marks the victory of the great concept of
"one country, two systems" put forward by Deng Xiaoping. It also
shows the diplomatic wisdom of the current third generation of
China's collective leadership, who overcame the obstacles imposed
by the British Hong Kong government during the transitional period
of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
With the return of Hong Kong, a trend toward improvement and
growth in Sino-British relations has also gradually emerged. The
good cooperation between China and Portugal on the issues
concerning Macao's return to China will serve for the smooth
handover of Macao and reflects the stable ties between China and
Portugal.
</P>
<P>
-- The successful implementation of the "one country, two
systems" concept is of great significance to the peaceful
reunification of the motherland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Open up New Prospect for China's Diplomacy in 1990s (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has been striving to establish fair and reasonable
international political and economic orders.
</P>
<P>
Toward this end, China has actively participated in
multilateral and international activities. At international
affairs, China has safeguarded its sovereignty, upheld justice and
opposed hegemony and power politics.
</P>
<P>
As a permanent member of the UN Security Council, China has
played a unique and active role in UN affairs.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li Peng join multilateral
diplomatic activities. In the past four years, Jiang attended the
informal meeting of the APEC leaders every year. Premier Li
attended the Asia-Europe Summit, the Social Development Summit and
the World Food Summit.
</P>
<P>
China successfully hosted the UN Fourth World Conference on
Women in 1995 and the 96th Interparliament Conference in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Through these activities, China has won extensive support from
the international community on issues about sovereignty and
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Chinese leaders clearly expounded at many international
occasions China's position and principled stand on the
establishment of new international political and economic orders.
</P>
<P>
China holds that:
</P>
<P>
-- All countries - big or small, strong or weak, rich or poor -
are equal members of the international community and have the
right to participate in and handle international affairs;
</P>
<P>
-- All countries have the right to choose their own social
system, ideology, economic mode and development path;
</P>
<P>
-- All countries should respect each other's sovereignty and
territorial integrity, maintain mutual non-aggression and
non-interference in each other's internal affairs;
</P>
<P>
-- International conflicts should be settled peacefully through
dialogues, and all forms of bullying and pressuring by big, strong
and rich powers on small, weak and poor ones should be opposed;
</P>
<P>
-- All countries should abide by the principle of equality,
mutual benefit, mutual support, mutual advancement, and mutual
complement with each other's strong points in economic changes and
in global and regional economic cooperation, and should
not discriminate against each other or practice trade protectionism
of any form, let alone impose sanctions from time to time; and
</P>
<P>
-- The developed nations have the responsibility to help the
developing countries to boost their economy in an effort to narrow
the North-South gap.
</P>
<P>
In the area of human rights, China advocates dialogue and
cooperation and opposes using human rights as an excuse for
interfering into other countries' internal affairs. This position
represents the aspiration of the developing countries and is
supported by the international community.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, China has, for seven times, frustrated the
anti-China act proposed by a small number of western countries at
the Geneva Conference on Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
China also actively participated in the process of disarmament,
making a active contribution to comprehensive and thorough
disarmament. China actively joined the talks and played an active
part in forming the treaty for a complete ban on nuclear tests and
becomes one of the first group of countries to sign the treaty.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China has reiterated many times its defensive
policy of national defense and refuted the so-called "China
threat" notion spread purposely by a small number of people
abroad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Open up New Prospect for China's Diplomacy in 1990s (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's all-round diplomatic work has served the growth of its
national economy.
</P>
<P>
After the Cold War, the role of economic factors has become
more prominent in international relations and more countries are
shifting their strategic focus to economy, and the world economy
is entering a daily close cooperation.
</P>
<P>
With this in the background, the third generation of Chinese
leaders work to make the country's diplomatic work serve the focus
of developing the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The CPC, the National People's Congress (NPC) and
non-governmental organizations have all seen to it that exchanges
with their foreign counterparts serve to create a favorable
environment for building socialism with Chinese characteristics
and a socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
Chinese leaders regarded developing bilateral economic and
trade ties as an important mission of their visits to other
countries and took every opportunity to promote China's
participation in regional and world economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The fast, sustainable and healthy growth of China's economy for
more than a decade, with the help of "economic diplomacy," has
accelerated the development of the economy and trade between China
and other countries.
</P>
<P>
China has become the world's biggest potential market and one
of the countries which used much foreign capital since the
beginning of the 1990s. More and more countries support China's
entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
The CPC has established relations and conducted friendly
exchanges with more than 300 political parties in over 120
countries throughout the world. Those political parties not only
include ruling parties but also parties not in power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Open up New Prospect for China's Diplomacy in 1990s (7) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The foreign contacts of the NPC effectively serves China's
central task of economic construction. The NPC has played an
important role in helping China to participate in international
political and economic affairs, in expanding the mutual
understanding and cooperation between China and other countries in
various fields, and in promoting the development of China's
relations with foreign countries. The NPC has so far established
links with parliaments in some 40 countries and set up bilateral
friendship groups with over 40 foreign parliaments.
</P>
<P>
The NPC has become a member or observer of some parliamentary
organizations and conferences such as the Inter-Parliament Union,
the Asia-Pacific Parliamentary Forum and the Asian Forum of
Parliamentarians on Population and Development.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC)
has also become an important force in promoting the development of
relations between China and other countries.
</P>
<P>
The 21st Century Forum, hosted by the CPPCC in 1996, attracted
statesmen from dozens of countries all over the world, who
discussed regional security, economic cooperation and other major
issues. The forum helped increased mutual understanding between
countries concerned.
</P>
<P>
In addition, non-government foreign contacts at different
levels have conducted various forms of friendly exchanges with
other countries in economy, trade, science, technology and
culture, contributing to the overall development of China's
foreign relations.
</P>
<P>
There are now some 700 pairs of sister cities between China and
other countries.
</P>
<P>
The verses of a poem by late Chinese leader Mao Zedong
accurately describe China's successes in its foreign relations in
recent years:
</P>
<P>
"The day will soon break in the east, Say not 'you are an early
bird to start.' Having traversed all the hills I am not old in
the least, Only to find the scenery here plays the fairest part."
</P>
<P>
At the turn of the century, the third generation of Chinese
leaders appear ready to face all challenges and opportunities in
the international situation and are fully confident they can bring
a prosperous and strong China into the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
