<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Foreign Reserves Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' gross
international reserves (GIR) rose to 10.55 billion U.S. dollars as
of September 2, after a currency crisis reduced the country's
reserves by 1 billion dollars nearly two months ago.
</P>
<P>
"This is a significant 1 billion dollar recovery from the July
18 level of 9.3 billion dollars, a week after the bank announced
that it was allowing the foreign exchange rate to move within a
wider band," Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson said in a
statement released here today.
</P>
<P>
He said the amount of the current international reserves is
equivalent to about 2.8 months' imports of goods and services for
the country.
</P>
<P>
Singson attributed the latest recovery to the International
Monetary Fund's Extended Fund Facility amounting to 700 million
dollars, and deposits of the loan proceeds from the Japanese
Eximbank IMF Parallel Loan and the purchase of proceeds from the
Development Bank of the Philippines' bond floatation.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines' gross international reserves declined to 9.3
billion dollars by July 18 after the central bank spent 1.9
billion dollars in 40 days on defending the peso against
speculators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
