<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 10:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rafsanjani Criticizes Turkey for Joint War Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Iran's former president Hashemi
Rafsanjani today criticized Turkey for holding joint naval
maneuvers with Israel and the United States "at a time when
Israeli forces are continuing their attacks on Lebanon."
</P>
<P>
He expressed regret that Turkey, "a large Muslim nation
with 60 million Muslim, will be holding military maneuvers with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Now chairman of the State Expediency Council to advise
incumbent President Mohammad Khatami on policies-making,
Rafsanjani made the remarks in his sermon to the Friday prayers at
Tehran University.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Foreign Ministry on Wednesday strongly denounced the
Israel-US-Turkey joint military maneuvers scheduled for
mid-November in east Mediterranean off the coast of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi said "Iran
considers Turkey a member of the Islamic community and rejects
its cooperation with the Zionist regime as detrimental to the
interests of Muslims in the region."
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Syria have already expressed their opposition to
the Israel-US-Turkey war games.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to soothe the anger of its Arab neighbors, Ankara
has repeated said the exercises were for search and rescue
operations and not directed against any other country.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani also criticized Arab countries for being "easily
tricked by Israel." The Arabs should have continued to
boycott Israel and should have never established ties with
Israel through agreements, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Arabs who fasted for 50 years, who boycotted, and refused
to talk, with Israel, ... broke their fast with sinful food," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
