<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Trade Balance Worsens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's import bill
amounted to 126.4 million U.S. Dollars compared to 42.2 million
Dollars earned from exports, representing a yawning trade deficit
of 84.2 million Dollars in the first seven months this year.
</P>
<P>
According to Bank of Tanzania (BOT), the trade deficit rose to
48.5 million Dollars from last January's 33.7 million Dollars,
and it scaled further to 76.7 million Dollars in the following
month.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's Monthly Economic Review for August 1997,
which is available here this week, said that exports have
unceasingly shrunk since the beginning of the year. By July the
country realized less than half of what it spent on imports.
</P>
<P>
BOT attributed the yawning trade deficit to poor performance
of traditional commodities and a simultaneous increase in the
import bill.
</P>
<P>
The poor performance of traditional export crops is attributed
to drought that hit the country toward the end of last year and
early this year. Many regions have since reported crop failure
and the country is on the verge of famine as a result of the
below normal rainfall this year.
</P>
<P>
Among the traditional cash earners, chiefly coffee, cotton,
tobacco, sisal, tea and cashew nuts, only sisal and tea recorded
increases in export volumes in July as compared to June.
</P>
<P>
However, earnings from the few non-traditional exports,
including minerals, manufactured goods, cotton yarn, processed
coffee and horticultural products, have been rising.
</P>
<P>
The central bank is of the view that the country's economy
could have been healthier if it diversified its exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
