<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Host NGO Forum on Social Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 5 (Xinhua) -- About 50 non-governmental
organizations (NGOs) will meet next week in Malaysia with the aim
of strengthening their role in the implementation of the "agenda
for action on social development" in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The three-day forum, to be held from September 8 to 10 in Kuala
Lumpur, will decide on a set of recommendations to be submitted to
governments at the Fifth Asian and Pacific Ministerial Conference
on Social Development in Manila from November 5 to 11, 1997,
according to a press release issued today by the U.N. Economic and
Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP).
</P>
<P>
The forum will also facilitate the participation of NGOs in
preparatory activities for the Manila conference through a report
on the Kuala Lumpur NGO forum.
</P>
<P>
The forum will take stock of their contribution to poverty
alleviation, employment expansion and social integration, and the
constraints NGOs face.
</P>
<P>
The Manila conference is to take place in response to ESCAP and
U.N. General Assembly resolutions referring explicitly to the need
for active multisectoral implementation of the outcome of the
World Summit for Social Development which the coming conference
will focus on, said Edward van Roy, director of the ESCAP Social
Development Division.
</P>
<P>
Van Roy added that ESCAP is fully prepared to facilitate
regional coordination between the region's governments and NGOs in
promoting continuing dialogue regarding planning, implementation
and evaluation of the regional social development agenda.
</P>
<P>
The agenda for social development, adopted in 1994, identifies
specific time-bound regional social development goals, targets and
agreements on their attainment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
