<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Builds First BOT Power Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Construction of the Laibin
Power Plant, the country's first foreign-funded power project
using the Build-Operate-Transfer (BOT) method, commenced today
in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The consortium of Electricite de France (EDF) and GEC Alsthom
won the contract in round of international bidding in 1995, and
signed an agreement with the local government on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the plant is scheduled for completion in the
year 2000. The plant, with two 360-megawatt thermal power
generating units, is expected to ease the region's increasing
demand for power.
</P>
<P>
The plant will built at a cost of 600 million US dollars, some
25 percent of which will be provided by the consortium.
</P>
<P>
The consortium will operate the plant for 18 years after
completion and then transfer the facility to the Guangxi
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
