<HEADLINE> Saitoti Denounces Violences in Kenya's Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Vice-President George
Saitoti today said his government had denounced recent violent
actions in the port city of Mombasa and its environs, the Kenyan
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted him as saying in London that the government
is working swiftly to restore law and order in the violence hit
areas in the Coast Province.
</P>
<P>
Saitoti who is also Minister for Planning and National
Development reiterated that whoever was involved in the mayhem in
Likoni and other places in the coast areas would be dealt with
law.
</P>
<P>
He defended the Kenyan government from complicity in the
lawless actions which occurred in Coast Province during the past
fortnight.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan leader underlined the government's commitment to
constitutional reforms contrary to wrong impression that there
were hard-liners in the ruling Kenya African National Union
(KANU) who were opposed to reforms.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed the National Convention Executive Council (NCEC)
as a body with no mandate to hold constitutional reforms talks
with KANU.
</P>
<P>
The NCEC, an umbrella body of reform activists and Opposition
parties, yesterday released its mass action program to force the
government to initiate "meaningful dialogue" for the
constitutional reforms before the general elections to be held
later this year.
</P>
<P>
In response, the Inter-Party Parliamentary Group (IPPG)
Thursday appealed to Kenyans to ignore calls for mass action by
the NCEC.
</P>
<P>
The IPPG comprising Members of Parliament from the ruling and
Opposition parties replaced the NCEC to undertake constitutional
reforms talk between KANU and Opposition parties. 
</P>
