<HEADLINE> U.N. Condemns Refugee Expulsion from Ex-Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. High Commissioner
for Refugees (UNHCR) has "vehemently condemned" the military
expulsion of Rwandan and Burundi refugees from the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The expulsion at predawn on Thursday is "a blatant breach of
international refugee treaties," said High Commissioner Sadako
Ogata in a statement available here today. She has also sent a
protest letter to DRC President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers surrounded the UNHCR transit center in Kisangani,
eastern DRC, at 4:00 a.m., herded all the occupants except a few
pregnant women to the airport to which they sealed off the route
and denied UNHCR access.
</P>
<P>
The transit center held 336 Rwandans and 353 Burundians
awaiting screening to determine who among them deserved formal
refugee status.
</P>
<P>
One aircraft carrying the first group thrown out of Kisangani
arrived at Rwandan capital Kigali at mid-morning on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The DRC government has simply ignored our pleas to allow
these people to be screened to establish if they were genuine
refugees deserving international protection. Such actions are
completely unacceptable," said Ogata.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 2,500 Rwandans in 10 different UNHCR
facilities in the central African country, about half of them
awaiting screening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Stock Exchange Not to Limit Stock Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Stock Exchange
(PSE) clarified today that it has not recommended the limiting of
stock sales to actual physical holdings of certificates.
</P>
<P>
Instead, PSE President Jose Luis Yulo said in a statement, the
PSE is finalizing rules and regulations for short selling.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to some newspaper reports that the PSE will limit
stock sales to cope with the recent decline of the stock market,
Yulo said that PSE will not ask for a lock-up period for foreign
funds invested in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that he only suggested ways to expand and deepen
the local investor base by way of developing the mutual fund
industry, and to find a mechanism for government and private local
funds to invest in the market.
</P>
<P>
Yulo recommended on Thursday that the solution to stock market
woes should be to get government and local private funds to invest
in the equities market, particularly when there is an outflow of
foreign funds.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Securities and Exchange Commission asked the PSE
to explain why there was a sharp decline in the PSE Index,
especially after the July 11 peso depreciation whose effects have
somehow resulted in the prevailing currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Yulo further said the PSE called for the lowering or
eliminating of taxes on stock transactions, documentary stamp tax
and the value-added tax.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the principle of the PSE is to advocate for a
free and fair play of market forces in a global economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
