<HEADLINE> 11 ECOMOG Soldiers Killed in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has confirmed the death
of 11 soldiers of the west African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG)
when they ran into land mines planted by the military junta in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Another three peace-keepers were seriously wounded in land
mine blasts on Wednesday, according to a statement from the
ECOMOG headquarters in Liberia, which reached here today.
</P>
<P>
The peace-keepers conveying foodstuff from Lungi, where Sierra
Leone's international airport is located, to troops in Jui were
blown by the land mines planted around the farmland at Lungi
village, said the statement, faxed by the press secretary to
ECOMOG force commander, Biola Lawal.
</P>
<P>
Another statement of Nigeria's Defense Headquarters confirmed
Thursday that the junta had intensified the laying of land mines
on ECOMOG routes in Lungi to Freetown, Bo, Kenema and other
important towns in the hinterland.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, both the junta and ECOMOG were on Thursday
exchanging allegations of being attacked by the other side, which
reports said had claimed 50 lives with 120 injured as on Thursday
evening.
</P>
<P>
One account said the Nigerian-led ECOMOG troops had opened
fire at two container ships which violated the economic embargo
against the troubled country ordered by west African leaders.
</P>
<P>
But the Defense Headquarters in Lagos said the junta opened
fire on ECOMOG base at Lungi near Freetown as a fallout of
Wednesday's meeting between the junta leader Major Johnny Koroma
and his aides and military commanders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
