<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mitsubishi Engine Venture in China Gets Approval </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Mitsubishi Motors Corp
was approved by the Chinese government to set up a joint venture
in northeast China's Liaoning Province with four other partners
for the promotion of car engines and transmissions.
</P>
<P>
According to today's "China Daily", the venture, which involves
an investment of 8.86 billion yen (73 million U.S. dollars), is
jointly funded by the China Aerospace Automotive Industry Group
Company, the Shenyang Construction Investment Co., the Japanese
trading house Mitsubishi Corp, Malaysian firm MCIC Holdings Sdn
Bhd, and Mitsubishi Motors Corp, with the Chinese firms controling
51 percent of the stake, and the Japanese car maker holding 25
percent of the stake.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture is to produce 150,000 2-liter and 2.4-liter
gasoline engines and transmissions for rear-and front-drive
vehicles a year.
</P>
<P>
The business, which is one of the three engine projects
Mitsubishi plans to set up in China in the years to come, will
starts formal production in 1999. Its products will be used to
supply automobile makers in China.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, Mitsubishi has invested approximately
500 million U.S. dollars in 150 projects in China, focusing mainly
on power generating equipment, steel plants, and building
materials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
