<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Bank to Deal With Currency Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank
said today that it will take the necessary steps to deal with the
peso depreciation by introducing a package of monetary measures.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson said in a statement that
the measures are expected to strengthen the government's financial
policy to guard against further speculative attacks on the local
currency. But he did not give details of the measures.
</P>
<P>
The governor said the peso flotation is handled much better
this time than in 1990 and 1993, adding that full information on
the currency crisis has been provided to the public.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the government's price monitoring program has
been stepped up in key areas such as Metro Manila and other major
cities.
</P>
<P>
To avoid unnecessary pressure from the industrial sector, the
government maintained close links with labor and management,
banks, and even oil firms to ensure that nothing would get out of
control, he said.
</P>
<P>
Singson expressed confidence that the peso depreciation which
took effect on July 11 will have minimal impact on the country's
inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
Price increase is less than half of the July 1996 level of 8.9
percent, thus bringing the average inflation rate for the
January-July period to 4.63 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that the July inflation will trace a
continually reasonable inflation path for the rest of the year,"
Singson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
