<HEADLINE> China Reports Early Rice Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- China's early rice harvest has
hit 45.78 million tons, up 4.5 percent on last year, according to
a report released here today by the State Statistical Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Seven of the country's nine major producers of early rice
reported output increases, with the sole exceptions being Jiangxi
and Zhejiang provinces.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the good harvest to the widespread use of
agricultural science and technology. The per hectare output jumped
by some 320 kg, with a 2.6 million ton total increase in output of
early rice.
</P>
<P>
Governments at all levels played a major role in the harvest.
For example, Guangdong Province introduced a seed project and
provided four million yuan in funding to establish a seed risk
fund. Fujian Province allocated 130 million yuan to continue an
ongoing project to transform 30 counties into grain production
bases, and promote grain self-sufficiency in an additional 23
counties.
</P>
<P>
Stable prices for agricultural production equipment and
materials also contributed to the good harvest. Price indices for
agricultural materials dropped nationwide, with the sole exception
of an 0.8 percent rise in the price index for pesticides.
</P>
<P>
Relatively good weather conditions also contributed to this
year's early rice harvest.
</P>
<P>
Chinese farmers planted early rice on 8.16 million ha, down
some 120,000 ha on 1996. According to the report, the reduced area
was mainly due to the falling grain prices which accompanied the
previous year's harvest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Economies to Be on Track of Growth Soon: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The chief executive of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), today expressed the
confidence that Asian economies will soon be back on the path of
prosperity, despite recent financial turmoil in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
"The fundamentals of the Asian economies are good. Therefore we
should not lose heart. I am sure that we will soon be back on the
path to prosperity," Tung Chee Hwa said while addressing 400
leading businessmen, government officials and diplomats at a
luncheon talk here on "Hong Kong After the Transition."
</P>
<P>
The recent turmoil in Southeast Asian financial and stock
markets has come as a blow to many hopes in the region and this is
a deep frustration felt by all, he said, adding that Hong Kong,
likewise, did not escape the speculative pressures.
</P>
<P>
However, "we should not lose sight of the fact that the opening
up of our economies and markets has brought great benefits," he
said. But he was quick to add that it is also important to
remember that "the process does mean becoming open, as well, to
pressures from outside, pressures that can expose our internal
weaknesses."
</P>
<P>
He said Hong Kong learned, as a leading financial center in
Asia, that the proper response to these pressures is to regulate
properly.
</P>
<P>
"Our experience is that the risks of the open market can be
managed by making the market operate as transparently and
efficiently as possible, by maintaining financial discipline in
the public sector, and by ensuring that financial institutions
manage their investments and risks properly," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Tung has been here since Thursday on a three-day visit and is
scheduled to wind up his Southeast Asia tour Saturday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
