<HEADLINE> Tung: Boosting HK Economic Vitality Foremost Task </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chief Executive of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) Tung Chee Hwa
said here today that the foremost task of his administration is to
enhance Hong Kong's economic vitality and sustain economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"My government will create a business environment and provide
an educated and well-trained workforce that will promote the
services sector and the development of value-added and high
technology industries," Tung said at a luncheon talk on "Hong Kong
After the Transition" attended by 400 leading businessmen,
government officials and diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting education as the key to the future of Hong Kong,
the chief executive said his government is aiming to give every
child in Hong Kong "a modern, well-balanced education of the
highest quality, to extend opportunities for lifetime learning and
retraining."
</P>
<P>
"We trust that Hong Kong may become a center for excellence in
education in Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that ownership of a home is crucial for personal
security and social stability, Tung said his government will speed
up reclamation and land formation over the next 10 years and
increase substantially the production of housing units.
</P>
<P>
"We will increase overall housing supply at a target of not
less than 85,000 flats a year and aim to achieve a home ownership
rate of 70 percent in 10 years," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the SAR government is paying particular attention
to the rising population of the elderly. He said his
administration has set up a "Commission for the Elderly" and is
developing "a comprehensive policy to provide them with a sense of
security, a sense of belonging and a sense of worthiness."
</P>
<P>
He said that during his visit here, he is particularly
interested in the fields of education and housing.
</P>
<P>
According to a spokesman of Tung's delegation, housing,
education and information technology were the focus of the talks
between Tung and Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong on
Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
During the hour-long talks, described by a Singapore Foreign
Ministry spokesman as "warm and friendly," Tung and Goh discussed
Singapore's housing policy, especially in regard to price
stabilization.
</P>
<P>
On education, the two leaders focused on the medium of
instruction and the promotion of bilingual education.
</P>
<P>
This morning, Tung visited Singapore's Chinese High School
where he was briefed by Minister for Education Teo Chee Hean on
Singapore's education policies. Tung is also scheduled to tour the
Toa Payoh housing estate in the central part of Singapore and
visit two families there this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Tung arrived here on Thursday for a three-day visit as part of
his first overseas trip since taking office on July 1. Before
Singapore, he visited Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Tung is scheduled to meet with Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew
later today and conclude his visit here on Saturday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
