<HEADLINE> Heavy Fighting Breaks Out in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting launched by
Lebanese army and resistance fighters against Israeli troops took
place again in south Lebanon early this morning, killing at least
12 Israeli soldiers, Lebanese security officials said.
</P>
<P>
However, this figure can not be independently confirmed.
</P>
<P>
The fighting began when two Israeli helicopters landed
commandos in the village of Insariyeh, more than 40 kilometers
south from Beirut and killed two civilians and wounded six,
Lebanese Orient Radio quoted the officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The village is believed to be used as a stronghold by the
Shiite Muslim militant Amal fighters, led by the country's House
Speaker Nabih Berri, to attack Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli raid was reported to be a retaliation for last
week's Amal attack in which five Israeli soldiers were killed.
</P>
<P>
Two Israeli gunships also joined the battle, strafing and
rocketing the nearby villages of Adloun and Saksakieh, also known
as Amal strongholds.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese army unleashed a heavy barrage of anti-aircraft fire
against the Israeli attacking gunships and four others that were
hovering to provide cover.
</P>
<P>
Hezbullah, or Party of God, quickly rushed fighters to help
their Amal allies, according to the security officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
