<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourism Grows Rapidly in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Tourism grew rapidly in China
in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the National Tourism Administration show that
China during this period received a total of 26.7 million overseas
tourists, an increase of 8.67 percent compared with the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Eight of China's 31 provinces, municipalities and autonomous
regions recorded a growth rate of over 45 percent in the tourism
sector, much higher than the national average. They are Hubei,
Hunan and Henan provinces in central China, Shanxi and Hebei
provinces in the north, Anhui province in the east, Heilongjiang
province in the northeast, and Yunan province in the
southwest. All of them were traditionally thought of as having
lukewarm tourist appeal.
</P>
<P>
Of them, the top three are Hubei, Anhui and Shanxi, with a
growth rate of 104 percent, 99 percent and 75 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Sun Gang, Vice Chairman of the National Tourism
Administration, deems that the high growth illustrates good
tourism prospects for those regions where scenic sites abound.
</P>
<P>
The growing interest of overseas tourists in the Chinese market
is another reason for the high growth. According to Sun, travel
agencies in Europe, North America, Japan and the Republic of Korea
have already made central and western China a focus for expansion
of their business.
</P>
<P>
Sun also attributed the progress to local governments'
attention on developing tourism. In the early 1990s,
many provincial governments listed tourism as a pillar industry
which enjoys preferential policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Why Southeast Asian Currencies Continue                    to Slide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Two months after a currency
crisis swept across Southeast Asia, there are no signs of an end
of the turmoil on the region's currency markets today and no one
can predict when Southeast Asian currencies will stop falling.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Malaysia's ringgit fell to a new record low of
2.991 against the U.S. dollar from Wednesday's close of 2.973
while the Philippine peso plunged to a new record low of 32.41
from 31.70 to the dollar and the Indonesian rupiah dived to an
all-time low of 3,060.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore dollar also slid to 1.5195 against the greenback
from Wednesday's close of 1.5185 while the Thai baht was traded at
35.45 offshore, down from 35.50.
</P>
<P>
During the past two months, Southeast Asian governments have
taken a series of measures to prevent the continuous fall of their
currencies, including central bank interventions in the markets,
higher interest rates and monetary disciplines to check
speculations.
</P>
<P>
However, none of these measures seems effective enough to check
the downward trend of the region's currencies.
</P>
<P>
Analysts cited a couple of reasons for the steady depreciation
of Southeast Asian currencies. One of them is a possible economic
slowdown in the region in the latter part of this year and in next
year, the first bitter pill Southeast Asian countries may have to
swallow after the currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Since the Thai currency crisis spilled over in the region in
early July, Southeast Asian currencies have devalued between 10
percent to over 20 percent. As one of the measures to stabilize
their currencies, central banks have raised interest rates. But
higher interest rates make it harder for companies to get the cash
they need to expand.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector in the region has already been hurt by
higher interest rates and higher cost of foreign debt payments due
to weaker currencies and a production slowdown is unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest forecast by economists, most Southeast
Asian countries would experience economic slowdowns in 1997 and
1998. Their growth rates would be a bit lower than the government
targets.
</P>
<P>
The signs of an economic slowdown in the region have undermined
the confidence of foreign investors, whose selling of currencies
in the region has caused the continuous market turmoil, economists
said.
</P>
<P>
The lack of joint efforts by Southeast Asian countries to
strike back at the speculators is another main reason for the
continuous fall of currencies in the region.
</P>
<P>
In the last two months, Southeast Asian countries intervened in
the markets whenever their currencies were under strong
speculative attack. But as their foreign reserves were limited and
their interventions were not a collective effort, these countries
could hardly succeed in defending their currencies.
</P>
<P>
Realizing the failure, Southeast Asian finance ministers will
meet in Bangkok on September 17 to discuss ways of dealing with
the crisis. The topics will include a proposal to set up an ASEAN
(Association of Southeast Asian Nations) fund that could be used
by member countries affected by currency instability.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the spillover effect is also a major factor which
often leads to currency falls in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Southeast Asian countries are facing some similar economic
problems, such as high current account deficit, oversupply of
office and residential buildings and huge non-performing bank
loans. Whenever a country's internal problems cause currency
falls, other currencies in the region will also be dragged lower
for psychological reasons.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, when debt default by Thailand's largest finance
company Finance One prompted the Thai baht to plummet by 7
percent, the Malaysian ringgit, the Indonesian rupiah and the
Philippine peso were also affected and hit record lows against the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
"There is no way one can be positive on Southeast Asian
currencies at this stage. The other Southeast Asian countries are
taking their cues from Thailand and developing their own internal
problems," said Vincent Low, a regional-currency strategist at
Merrill Lynch International Bank in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Judging from the current situation in the region, some
economists said the market turmoil may last at least another month
or two and Southeast Asian currencies could fall further.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Loans Alleviate Grain Storage Problems in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese banks have granted
loans with discounted interest to help alleviate grain storage
problems in major grain producing areas in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
The successive grain harvests in recent years have resulted in
the lack of adequate grain storage depots. According to recent
estimates, almost half of harvested grain is stored in the open
air for extended periods.
</P>
<P>
However, since the end of last year, state banks have issued
special loans of 950 million yuan (11.45 million US dollars) to
help expand the grain storage capacity of Liaoning, Jilin and
Heilongjiang provinces in the northeast and the Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region in the north.
</P>
<P>
The funds are mainly used to construct simple granaries, rent
idle buildings for storing grain and expanding and maintaining
existing granaries.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that the funds will help to expand the total
storage capacity by 1.5 billion kilograms of grain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
