<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chittagong Ship Owners Remove Congestion Surcharge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Vessel owners have withdrawn a
punitive congestion surcharge at Bangladesh's largest Chittagong
Port with effect from the first day of this month, port sources
said today.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore-based Chittagong Feeder Trade Committee (CFTC)
has informed port authorities of the decision, saying there was an
improvement and a reduction in congestion at this South Asian
country's key seaport in August.
</P>
<P>
The removal of the surcharge came after repeated appeals of the
port authorities.
</P>
<P>
"Despite economic losses, we will be withdrawing the Chittagong
Port congestion surcharge with retrospective effect from September
1 with vessels departing from Singapore, Colombo and Chittagong."
the committee said in a fax message to port authorities.
</P>
<P>
The feeder operators have imposed congestion surcharge from
time to time since 1992 as a result of shortage of container
handling equipment and space in container yards and unusual
strikes.
</P>
<P>
Chittagong Port witnessed heavy congestion in July mainly due
to a strike by trade unions, incessant rainfall and shortage of
space.
</P>
<P>
The annoyed vessel owners on August 16 imposed the surcharge
for one month with a rate of 150 U.S. dollars for a 20-foot
container and 300 dollars for a 40-foot container per day, as a
cost-recovery measure against overstay of ships at the port.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
