<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fresh Violence in Kenya Kills Four </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Four Kenyans have been killed
in fresh violence hitting Likoni, located in the Indian Ocean
port Mombasa, and southwestern Gucha-Trans Mara districts, local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Three people were killed with at least 12 seriously injured in
recent separate boundary clashes in Gucha-Trans Mara Districts
where youths from the Maasai and Kisii communities engaged in a
fierce fight, said the report.
</P>
<P>
One up-country person was shot dead by armed raiders in Likoni
Thursday. The gunmen also set ablaze an unoccupied wholesale
shop, 300 meters from the burnt down Likoni police station where
six police had been killed on August 13.
</P>
<P>
Likoni residents said the attackers were armed with guns,
bows, arrows and pangas and resembled the raiders who have been
terrorizing the area two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
However, the police in Likoni said the attack was an isolated
case of robbery, denying that it was linked to the wave of terror
at the coast.
</P>
<P>
Another group of raiders, also unidentified, burnt down a
hotel and two residential houses in Likoni Thursday, while
leaving leaflets asking all inland communities to leave.
</P>
<P>
By Thursday, the fourth day of the third term, Likoni schools
remained empty.
</P>
<P>
Violence in the coastal districts in Kenya in the second half
of August claimed at least 46 lives and dealt a serious blow to
the tourism industry with hotels closed and foreigners canceling
booking.
</P>
<P>
Usually at least 5,000 tourists arrive in Mombasa weekly
during this season but now the number has fallen drastically by
between 30 and 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Tourism industry is the number one foreign exchange earner for
the east African country which received 770,000 visitors last
year with an earning of 480 million U.S. Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
