<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Foreign Missions in Financial Trouble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Eleven Ugandan foreign
missions are getting into financial trouble, local media reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Elly Karuhanga, chairman of the Parliamentary Committee on
Presidential Affairs, told the committee's meeting yesterday that
he had received complaints from Ugandan envoys in London, Bonn,
Copenhagen, Geneva, Rome, Ottawa, Washington, Paris, New York,
Havana and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Martin Aliker, state minister for foreign affairs, confirmed
the difficult financial situation of the concerned missions.
</P>
<P>
In their fax messages to Karuhanga, the envoys complained the
slow response to their financial demands. The missions face
stoppage of supply of water and power due to the arrears, the
messages said.
</P>
<P>
Aliker told the meeting that the Foreign Ministry has no
enough money to divide among foreign missions.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Nabeta, permanent secretary of the Foreign Ministry,
told the meeting that his ministry was reducing the staff number
at the foreign missions. He said 50 percent of the staff is back
to Uganda. Even visiting Ugandan delegations are reduced to save
the fund, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Aliker revealed that the Ugandan Foreign Ministry has a fund
of 100 million Ugandan Shillings (some 100 thousand U.S. Dollars)
for its foreign missions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Urges Earnest Implementation of Water Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Wang Hanbin, one of China's
highest ranking legislators, has called for the earnest
implementation of the Water Law in order to better deal with the
problems of grave water shortages and water pollution.
</P>
<P>
Wang, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress (NPC) issued the call prior to the legislature's
fact-finding missions to check law enforcement efforts in
Heilongjiang, Henan and Hunan provinces.
</P>
<P>
Wang acknowledged that the country has scored remarkable
achievements in water conservancy construction and the protection
of water resources since the Water Law went into effect in
1988. Success has also been achieved in combating serious flooding
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
However, Wang pointed out that success has been costly in terms
of financial and human resources, and outdated water conservancy
facilities on major rivers and lakes are inadequate for battling
major flooding.
</P>
<P>
He noted that water shortages and water pollution continue to
impede national economic development and pose a threat to the
health and well-being of the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
According to Ministry of Water Resources, the agriculture
sector suffers from an annual water shortage of 30 billion cubic
meters. There is six billion cubic meter shortfall for industrial
production, losing some 200 billion yuan in industrial output
value.
</P>
<P>
This year's droughts in northern and northeast China have
affected over 20 million ha. of crops, with sections in the middle
and lower reaches of the Yellow River remaining dry for 137
consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
Serious pollution levels prevent many cities from using water
from nearby rivers.
</P>
<P>
"Protecting water resources is imperative because of their
direct bearing on sustainable economic development," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
He urged NPC fact-finding groups to closely monitor the
situation, introduce timely solutions to problems, and summarize
experience in the realm of law enforcement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Urges U.S. to Withdraw Shipping Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Transport Minister
Makoto Koga today urged the United States to immediately revoke
sanctions it imposed on Japanese shipping firms.
</P>
<P>
A unilateral system of U.S. fines affecting Japan's three
largest shipping companies went into effect late Thursday to
punish alleged restrictive practices in Japanese ports.
</P>
<P>
Koga was quoted as saying by a Kyodo news agency report that
Japan will swiftly consider what measures it should take.
</P>
<P>
"In consultation with the Foreign Ministry, the Transport
Ministry may have to think about some kind of measures to stop
U.S. sanctions ... which means we may seek negotiations between
the two governments," Koga said.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Japanese Foreign Minister Yukihiko Ikeda issued a
warning in his statement that the sanctions "could have a serious,
adverse impact on Japan-U.S. economic relations."
</P>
<P>
Under the sanctions, Japan's Nippon Yusen K.K., Mitsui O.S.K.
Lines Ltd. and Kawasaki Kisen Kaisha Ltd. must pay 100,000 U.S.
dollars each time one of their freighters enters a U.S. port.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were introduced by the U.S. Federal Maritime
Commission as ongoing talks in Tokyo on Japanese port reforms
failed to reach an agreement by the September 4 deadline.
</P>
<P>
The independent commission was complaining about what it
regards as two restrictions on competition.
</P>
<P>
One is Japan's "prior consultation" system in which any changes
in shipping practices must first be discussed with the Japan
Harbor Transportation Association (JHTA).
</P>
<P>
The JHTA represents harbor transport service companies
including port and terminal operators and stevedores.
</P>
<P>
The other is Japanese harbors' alleged discrimination against
U.S. carriers that have attempted to run their own operations in
Japanese ports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
