<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 07:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Arrests 2 Hamas Leaders, 8 Activists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian police has
arrested two Hamas leaders following Thursday's triple suicide
bombing in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
However, Israel continued charging that the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) is not doing enough to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that the two political leaders of the
Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) were arrested hours after
the three bombings in central Jerusalem's Ben Yehuda pedestrian
mall.
</P>
<P>
One of the two arrested was identified as Jabal Mansour from
the West Bank city of Nablus, and the other as Mahmad Musalah from
another West Bank city of Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the PNA also arrested eight other Hamas activists
and shut down a newspaper published by the militant group, the
radio said.
</P>
<P>
At least seven people, including three suicide bombers, were
killed and nearly 200 others wounded Thursday afternoon in the
powerful blasts claimed by Hamas.
</P>
<P>
Hamas also claimed responsibility for the July 30 twin bombings
in Jerusalem's Mahane Yehuda market that killed 17 people and
injured 170 others.
</P>
<P>
In his reaction late Thursday, PNA President Yasser Arafat in
Gaza condemned the triple bombing as "terrorist activities" which
were against the Israeli people, the Palestinian people and the
whole peace process.
</P>
<P>
PNA Cabinet Secretary Ahmed Abdel Rahman offered to resume full
security cooperation with Israel, a condition Israel placed on
continuing the peace process. The PNA would do its best to
investigate and apprehend the people behind the bombings, he said.
</P>
<P>
Israel reacted strongly to the triple bombing by reimposing
the total closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip, including the
internal travel ban on Palestinians in West Bank, which was just
eased in past few days.
</P>
<P>
To express its anger about what it called Arafat's reluctance
to fight terrorism, Israel refused to allow Arafat's helicopter to
fly from Gaza to Ramallah, where he was scheduled to convene the
weekly Cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's flights between Gaza and West Bank are coordinated
with Israeli security and aviation authorities under interim peace
deals signed since 1993.
</P>
<P>
This was the second time that Arafat's helicopter was grounded
by Israel. The first was last September after fierce
Israeli-Palestinian clashes following Israel's opening of a West
Wall underground tunnel.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, during a visit to
the wounded in a Jerusalem hospital Thursday, said that unless
the PNA changed its attitude toward the terrorist organizations,
the peace process would not continue.
</P>
<P>
He blasted Arafat for appeasing terrorists by "hugging and
embracing" senior political leaders of Hamas and the Islamic Jihad
during a recent meeting under the banner of "national unity."
</P>
<P>
He also attacked Palestinian security chief in West Bank Jibril
Rajoub for taking the same path by telling militant leaders that
they were brothers "in the same struggle."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu convened an emergency meeting with senior security
officials following the bombings to assess the situation. He is
also to reconvene the security meeting today to formulate further
moves against the PNA to step up pressure on fighting
terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
