<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Continued Efforts Pledged for Burundi Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Great
Lakes region have pledged continued efforts to solve the
conflicts in the central African country of Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The stand of the leaders was made public in a communique
issued last night in Dar es Salaam at the end of a summit of the
region, which is available today.
</P>
<P>
The regional leaders maintained that the Burundi crisis should
be solved through negotiation whose objective is to achieve a new
fraternity in the country based on the principles of democracy
and security for all.
</P>
<P>
The summit rejected an offer by Burundi mediator, former
Tanzanian President Julius Nyerere, to resign as demanded by
Burundi. And the next round of talks on the Burundi peace process
will be held in Arusha, northern Tanzania, later.
</P>
<P>
"The summit urged all the parties, including the Burundi
government to take part in those talks, which will be convened by
the facilitator, Mwalimu Julius Nyerere," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The summit called on the Burundi military administration to
halt the on-going trials, saying no trials should be held until a
negotiated solution is reached on how to deal with politically
motivated crimes in the country, including massacres committed
since 1993 specially.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the region also called for an unconditional release
of some detained politicians in Burundi so as to let them travel
freely and participate in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"Existing sanctions will be maintained. A special secretariat
will be set up to monitor the effectiveness of the sanctions,"
said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Leaders or their representatives from the Congo (K), Rwanda,
Uganda, Ethiopia, Zambia, Tanzania, Kenya, Zimbabwe, and OAU
Secretary General Salim A Salim took part in the regional summit.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi had stayed away from the
meeting in anger at countries he accuses of demanding tough
measures which they then fail to enforce. Regional experts say
that without Kenya's presence such decisions are unlikely and
would be meaningless if the most important economy in the region
was not actively involved.
</P>
<P>
Situation in Burundi has been worsened since june 1996 when
Major Pierre Buyoya's military regime took over power from a
civilian government in that central African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
