<HEADLINE> Israel May Cut Its 1998 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Finance Ministry
has decided to cut 2.3 billion Shekel (about 657 million U.S.
dollars) in the budget for 1998, the Jerusalem Post newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
This plan includes cuts of budget for each ministry, except
that of health, David Milgrom, head of the Finance Ministry's
budget department, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The cuts are "a continuation of our message that the government
should make itself smaller and that the business sectors should
flourish," he explained.
</P>
<P>
He said public health care institutions would be allowed to
raise fees, while child subsidies for middle and high income
families would be reduced.
</P>
<P>
The plan is to be presented to the Cabinet on Sunday, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Finance Minister Yaacov Neeman promised not
to raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
"The tax burden on the people is negative and hurts growth (of
the economy). Our goal is to promote growth," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
