<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Economy on Healthy Track: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- All the internationally
recognized indicators show that the economy of Bangladesh is on a
sound and healthy track and its prospects are bright, Bangladesh
Finance Minister Shah A. M. S. Kibria said recently.
</P>
<P>
The banking system has sanctioned industrial credit amounting
to 79.32 billion taka (about 18.03 billion U.S. dollars) and
disbursed 78.18 billion taka (about 17.77 billion dollars) in the
last fiscal year (1996-97), the minister said in an interview with
the local press.
</P>
<P>
The statement by the finance minister was aimed at rejecting
his predecessor's claim that the country's economy "may collapse
in two months if right steps are not taken," the local newspaper
Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that the working capital disbursed during
the last fiscal year was 66.6 billion taka (about 15.14 billion
dollars), which was about double the amount for the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the foreign investment situation, the minister said
foreign investors proposed to invest 1.054 billion dollars in the
1996-97 fiscal year (starting from July 1) while 17 projects
involving 53.53 million dollars were set up in the export
processing zones.
</P>
<P>
In the power sector, he stated that agreements have already
been signed to invest 400 million dollars while three more
contracts are going to be signed shortly for an investment of 700
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
An amount of 100 million dollars has already been invested in
the gas sector and an additional 270 million dollars will be put
in within a year or two, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
In the telecommunications sector, he said, a total of 175
million dollars has already been invested and the investment of
another 500 million dollars is expected to be made within next
three years.
</P>
<P>
The minister expressed satisfaction over the macroeconomic
situation and said the country's foreign exchange reserves now
stand at 1.713 billion dollars as against 1.6 billion dollars in
August.
</P>
<P>
"The overall picture of foreign investment is certainly bright
and the prophets of doom, who are lamenting the situation, are
going to be proved wrong," he stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
