<HEADLINE> Police Arrests Suspect Anti-bid Bomber </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, September 5 (Xinhua) -- A suspect bomber carrying an
explosive device was arrested near a statue used as the logo for
Stockholm's 2004 Olympic bid, local police said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Anders Frantz'n said policemen who were
monitering activities around at Milles sculpture garden made the
arrest just before midnight.
</P>
<P>
The garden is home to the Carl Milles statue of a man and the
winged horse Pegasus, which is used by the Stockholm Olympic
Committee as the symbol for its bid for the 2004 Summer Olympic
Games.
</P>
<P>
The 28-year-old man, who is known by police, was alleged to be
carrying a bag containing a brown package with a detonator taped
onto it.
</P>
<P>
The arrest came after eight arson attacks at various sports
venues around Stockholm this year and two bomb explosions at
stadiums last month.
</P>
<P>
A secret group called We Who Built Sweden claimed
responsibility for the bombs and threatened more action, saying
money should not be spent to host an Olympics but on social causes.
</P>
<P>
The International Olympic Committee will pick the host city of
the 2004 games in Lausanne, Switzerland, later on Friday from the
five candidate cities.
</P>
<P>
They are Stockholm, Athens, Buenos Aires, Cape Town and Rome.
</P>
</TEXT>
