<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Registers Low Inflation Rate in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines registered an
annual inflation rate of 4.5 percent in August, lower than the 4.8
percent posted in June and July, despite the peso's depreciation,
the National Statistic Office said today.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine peso depreciated from 26.1 to the U.S. dollar in
early July to 32.4 Thursday, but the inflation rate remained
surprisingly low for August.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price index was estimated at 241.1 in August, from
239.3 in July, the office said in a report released here.
</P>
<P>
On a year-on-year basis, it said, housing and repair recorded a
higher rate of 9.7 percent in the month from 9.4 percent in July,
while fuel and water increased by 8.9 percent, compared with 7.5
percent in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate for food alone slowed down to 0.6 percent in
August from 1.3 percent in July, the office said.
</P>
<P>
But on a month-on-month basis, prices edged up by 0.8 percent
in August from 0.1 percent in July, it said.
</P>
<P>
"The biggest influence on month-on-month inflation for August
1997 can be attributed to food, beverages and tobacco and fuel,
light and water," the office said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
