<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chang Beat Rios to Advance to Semifinals at U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Second seed Michael Chang of
the United States defeated 10th seed Marcelo Rios of Chile in five
sets Thursday night to fill the gap of the last semifinal berth at
the U.S. Open Tennis Championships at Flushing, New York.
</P>
<P>
Chang won the match in 7-5, 6-2, 4-6, 4-6, 6-3 in two hours and
58 minutes, surviving a stirring comeback by Rios to enter the the
semifinals for the second straight year.
</P>
<P>
In the decisive fifth set, Chang broke Rios in the eighth game,
hitting a backhand winner on break point. He closed out the match
in the next game, but had to fight off two break points before
using a forehand winner from the baseline to end it.
</P>
<P>
In Thursday's other quarterfinal match, Patrick Rafter of
Australia gained a straight sets victory over unseeded Magnus
Larsson of Sweden to advance to the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
Rafter, the 13th seed, defeated Larsson, 7-6 (7-4), 6-4, 6-2,
and will next meet Chang.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, fifth seeded Manon Bollegraf of the Netherlands and
Rick Leach of the United States took the first title of the 1997
U.S. Open when they defeated unseeded Mercedes Paz and Pablo
Albano of Argentina in a third set tiebreak to win the mixed
doubles championship.
</P>
<P>
In the men's double semifinals, 11th seed Jonas Bjorkman and
Nicklas Kulti of Sweden defeated Wayne Black of Zimbabwe and Jim
Grabb of the United States with 7-5, 7-6 (7-4).
</P>
<P>
Likewise in the women's double semifinals, third seed Lindsay
Davenport of the United States and Jana Novotna of the Czech
Republic beat second seed Martina Hingis of Switzerland and
Arantxa Sanchez Vicario of Spain 6-4, 6-3 to advance to the
final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
