<HEADLINE> Ottey to Race Against Jones in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Jamaican sprinter Merlene Ottey
and newly crowned world champion Marion Jones of the United States
will take on in the women's 100-meter showdown in the Tokyo
international athletic meeting here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 37-year-old Ottey, who finished in a disappointment seventh
in Athens after she did not hear the recall and hit the 50 meter
mark before she realised she was the only one running in a false
start.
</P>
<P>
She failed again to win her first-ever 100-meter world title.
She was overshadowed by American Gail Devers in the Barcelona and
Atlanta Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Jones emerged as the new sprint queen after the 21-year-old
American former basketball player won the photo finish final
against Zhanna Pintusevich of Ukraine with her personal best of
10.83.
</P>
<P>
To the disappointment of fans, Devers and fellow American
Atlanta Olympic bronze winner Gwen Torrence as well as Christine
Arron of France, fourth in the world championships, pulled out of
the Tokyo meeting.
</P>
<P>
A total of seven Atlanta Olympic winners, 13 world champions
and eight world record holders will take part in the 13 men's and
nine women's events in Tokyo. 
