<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thailand Holds Charter Draft Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh has called on the Constitution Drafting Assembly
(CDA) to cooperate with parliament to amend the constitution
draft.
</P>
<P>
During a joint house debate on the draft in parliament on
Thursday, he asked that, if the CDA admits that there are flaws in
the draft, whether it is possible for the points in dispute to be
amended with full support from the CDA, before the draft is put to
vote later this month.
</P>
<P>
The 99-member CDA, elected last December in nationwide
elections, was given 240 days to draft a charter, with the aim of
getting rid of money politics and political corruption in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The draft was completed in August ahead of its deadline and was
then submitted to parliament (the National Assembly) for approval
or disapproval.
</P>
<P>
According to regulations, the National Assembly can vote either
in favor of it or reject it. If it is rejected, it would go for
national referendum.
</P>
<P>
However, Chavalit's proposal received little support from MPs.
</P>
<P>
Anand Panyarachun, chairman of the Charter Drafting Committee
of the CDA, said the CDA had completed its work and it is now for
parliament to decide by itself what it would do to the draft. The
CDA will not take any part in its amendment.
</P>
<P>
Opposition leader Chuan Leekpai said the prime minister's move
was unconstitutional. Banharn Silpa-Archa, leader of the Chart
Thai Party, also in the opposition, said that any amendment to the
draft could only be done after its passage.
</P>
<P>
The charter draft, although with some clauses unacceptable to
some politicians and MPs, is generally welcomed by the public, in
particular students organizations, as a major step forward to
clean Thailand's political corruption.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 supporters of the draft demonstrated in front of
parliament on Thursday, the first day of the debate on the draft.
</P>
<P>
Another group, estimated at 15,000, among them grassroots
leaders, such as district and village heads, are expected to hold
a rally at the Parliament House today, to show their opposition to
the draft.
</P>
<P>
Fears have been mounting for weeks over the possibility of
violence between supporters and opponents of the charter draft.
</P>
<P>
Some political organizations have urged that parliament adopt
the draft in its entirety and make amendments wherever necessary
later on.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the debate focused on article 3, which states that
sovereign power "belongs to" the people, while the present
constitution holds that it "emanates from" the people.
</P>
<P>
It was argued that the new version could diminish the power of
the constitutional monarchy. One senator said if the power
"belongs to" the people, they can take it back from the monarchy
at will.
</P>
<P>
Opponents of the draft charter also identified technical errors
during the debate, a move allegedly trying to block the draft's
passage through parliament.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
