<HEADLINE> Mid-Air Collision Averted in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 5 (Xinhua) -- A mid-air collision between
an Indian Boeing 737 airliner and an Indian air force jet was
averted on Thursday due to the swift action taken by one of the
pilots, the Hindustan Times said today.
</P>
<P>
According to informed sources, the Boeing 737 coming from the
Indian-held Jammu on a scheduled flight with 100 passengers would
have collided with the air force jet if the latter's pilot had not
taken evasive action.
</P>
<P>
The two planes had a very narrow escape, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Boeing aircraft of the Alliance Air, a subsidiary of the
Indian airlines, was cruising in the air about 80 kilometers from
Delhi.
</P>
<P>
It was under Delhi control at the level of 2,900 feet when the
air force jet came from the left in the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
The Alliance Air pilot, the sources said, could not see the
plane coming from the opposite direction due to bad weather.
</P>
<P>
However, the air force pilot took quick action and turned his
plane to the left side wing of the Boeing 737 in just a couple of
seconds, thus averting a major tragedy.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the impact of the air force plane, as it
passed by, was felt by the passengers of the Boeing 737 jet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
