<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Japanese Firms See Big Loss As Baht Floats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Japanese firms operating in
Thailand have suffered huge losses in foreign exchange as the baht
depreciated sharply over the past two months.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,000 Japanese companies operating in Thailand have lost a
total of 1,000 billion yen (about 8.3 billion U.S. dollars) since
the baht floated on July 2, a senior official of the Japanese
External Trade Organization (JETRO) said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two months, the currency instability has
seriously affected businesses as operators had no choice but to
adopt wait-and-see attitude before the baht is stabilized, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers today reported that the losses that Japanese
firms in Thailand suffered varied depending on their import needs.
</P>
<P>
Japanese automobile companies in Thailand, which imported more
than 50 percent of their materials, have been among the hardest
hit, while electronics and electrical appliance manufacturers
suffered less because they applied more local materials.
</P>
<P>
Companies which sold more locally than abroad are in worse
shape than those which sold more abroad.
</P>
<P>
Despite the losses, Japan will continue to roll over foreign
exchange loans given to companies in Thailand, Hayashi said.
</P>
<P>
Loans from Japanese financial institutions reportedly accounted
for about half of the total 72 billion dollar foreign currency
debts borrowed by the private sector in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's total foreign currency debts currently stand at
around 90 billion dollars and 37 billion of the total is in
short-term loans which will mature over the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
However, Hayashi said, more conditions will be attached to the
rolled-over loans in a bid to protect the lenders.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed hopes that the Thai government would address
its political problems to help ease the currency instability.
</P>
<P>
The baht so far has plunged by about 47 percent since July 2,
due to the strong dollar and the pending censure debate to be
launched by the opposition next Monday against Prime Minister
Chavalit Yongchaiyudh. The Thai central bank Thursday quoted its
reference rate above 38 baht against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The current Southeast Asian currency crisis has hit Japanese
firms in Thailand harder than elsewhere in the region as Japan has
the largest amount of investment in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Expecting the Thai economy will recover within the next two
years, Hayashi said that the immediate outlook remain uncertain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
