<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Still Having Chances to Reap Autumn Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- It is still too early to
predict a decline in China's grain harvest for this autumn, in
spite of a severe drought, a Ministry of Agriculture official
said.
</P>
<P>
If predicted weather conditions prevail, the situation
regarding grain crops is expected to improve, and there is still
time for rice crops to recover in south China, the China Daily
quoted Zhao Hanjie as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Since July, vast areas of northern China and the middle and
lower reaches of the Yangtze River have been hit by drought. By
the end of August, 9.3 million ha of crops were still suffering
from drought, nearly half of which were said to be in serious
danger.
</P>
<P>
"Drought in north China this summer has caused severe damage to
grain crops, especially maize, in some places," Zhao said. In its
key growth period, some maize did not even bear fruit.
</P>
<P>
But in most provinces, weather forecasts show that the first
frost will come at the normal time or later. Generally, the
earliest frost does not hit China until after September 20, Zhao
said.
</P>
<P>
It is too soon to say whether there will be an overall
reduction in the grain harvest this year, as there was an increase
of 10.7 million tons of grain in the summer harvest, he said.
</P>
<P>
To safeguard the harvest, field management is expected to be
strengthened. Measures will include increased irrigation of dry
areas.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, meteorologists predicted that the drought will
continue through the first 10 days of September in spite of
increased rainfall in some areas of northeast and south China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
