<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Banks Quit Thailand's Fund Recycling Schemes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Foreign banks have quitted
deposits recycling schemes brokered by the Bank of Thailand which
are designed to help create a clearing balance among the banks in
the country, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
However, Bank of Thailand governor Chaiyawat Wibulswasdi said
that his bank will proceed with the scheme together with local
commercial banks, but without the participation of foreign banks,
according to The Nation.
</P>
<P>
The Thai central bank early last month announced to carry out a
liquidity fund scheme and a deposit insurance fund scheme, which
require banks seeing rising deposits to transfer part of their
funds to those banks experiencing deposit runs.
</P>
<P>
Some banks, especially foreign banks, said that they will not
participate in the schemes as the Thai central bank does not want
to provide guarantees for loans made through the schemes, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Some banks also said that lending through the schemes may cause
the proportion of loans extended to a bank to exceed the lending
limit, which is 25 percent of the lender's capital, according to
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they stressed that they have to put aside their
excess liquidity to increase their reserves.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said that the schemes are impractical,
particularly as lenders will be concerned about the risk of
others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
