<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Develop Agriculture in Northern State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is urging private
entrepreneurs to invest in the agricultural sector in the northern
Shan state to develop the region and contribute to national
economic progress.
</P>
<P>
At a workshop held Thursday in Lashio in Shan state,
Lieutenant-General Tin Oo, second secretary of Myanmar's governing
body the State Law and Order Restoration Council, called for
endeavors for development of agriculture in the region which is
rich in resources with 364,500 hectares of arable land and 162,000
hectares of fallow land, The New Light of Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
He called for effective implementation of the project for
cultivation of poppy substitute crops after the end of
insurgencies in the region.
</P>
<P>
He also called for more investment in the promising services of
agriculture, livestock and fishery, and industrial sectors as well
as the trade sector.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, 75 percent of Myanmar's
overall production and services come from the private sector,
which also contributes 50 percent of the country's investment and
60 percent of the total export yearly.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that Myanmar's gross domestic product grew
by 5.8 percent in the 1996-97 fiscal year ending March, in which
agriculture production grew by 3.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The paddy product of the country in the fiscal year was
recorded at 17.08 million tons with rice export of 93,100 tons.
Paddy output in the 1995-96 fiscal year was 17.95 million tons
with 354,000 tons of rice exported.  
</P>
</TEXT>
