<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Inflation Rate Lowered to 1.5 Percent in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 4 (Xinhua) -- With retail prices remaining
unchanged for a third consecutive month this year, Italy's
inflation was lowered to 1.5 percent in August, compared to 1.6
percent in July, national statistics institute Istat reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The average rate of inflation for the first eight months was
1.9 percent, in line with government forecast of an average rate
of less than 2 percent for the entire year.
</P>
<P>
Istat noted that in August food prices had fallen by 0.1
percent while prices remained unchanged in the sectors of
clothing, furniture, health, entertainments, hotels, restaurant
and bars.
</P>
<P>
Compared to July prices, the biggest increases came in water
and electricity, housing and transports, all of which rose 0.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
Compared to a year ago, the biggest increases were in house
prices which increased 5.6 percent, education costs which grew 3.5
percent and in the health sector which saw a 3.3 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
For blue-collar and office workers, consumer prices rose by an
average of 2.2 percent over the year.
</P>
<P>
But analysts noted that the annual inflation rate had been more
than halved, passing from 3.4 percent in August 1996 to 1.5
percent in the same month this year.
</P>
<P>
The present level of inflation was the lowest since the spring
of 1969, it said, adding that Italy's 1.5 percent was also lower
than the 2 percent registered in Germany in August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
