<HEADLINE> Official: Outside Assistance Facilitates Tibet's Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- A senior Tibetan official said
that rapid economic and social development in Tibet is the result
of constant assistance from the central government and inland
provinces and regions, including aid in terms of human resources.
</P>
<P>
Qaicham Norbu, Chairman of the Tibetan Autonomous Regional
People's Government, called officials from other parts of China
who have helped with the local economy "the fresh blood" of the
region's development.
</P>
<P>
"They are sent not in a way of a systematic migration as
described by some hostile foreign forces," the chairman pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
He told vice governor of Jiangsu Province Ji Yunshi who visited
the region recently that the selfless aid from inland provinces
and regions, including Jiangsu, has contributed to Tibet's rapid
social and economic development and "Tibet is now experiencing the
best period in history."
</P>
<P>
Ji was on an inspection tour last week to Tibet, where the east
China province has invested around 200 million yuan (about 25
million US dollars) over the past two years to help build
hospitals, schools, training centers as well as a Tibetan
pharmaceutical factory.
</P>
<P>
Accompanying Ji were officials from provincial economic
departments who were to offer suggestions for Tibet's development
as well as concrete cooperation projects.
</P>
<P>
"We were not sure at first whether our investment in Tibet
would be practical and welcome," said the visiting vice
governor. "Now we are convinced that our projects have yielded
positive results."
</P>
<P>
Ji promised another 10 million yuan to help finance the
construction of a hospital for women and children and the
renovation of a main street in Lhasa.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu is among 14 provinces and cities entrusted by the
central government to render assistance to Tibet.
</P>
<P>
"It is obvious that Tibet's development cannot be achieved
without their assistance," Qaicham Norbu said, adding that Tibet
achieved a GDP valued at 6.5 billion yuan last year, with a growth
rate outpacing the nation's average for the first time. The per
capita income in Tibet last year exceeded 900 yuan.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Tibet needs the support of the whole country and
Tibetan people hope to build a better Tibet with people from other
ethnic nationalities.
</P>
<P>
"It is the fundamental aspiration of Tibetan people and cannot
be shaken by any rumors and irresponsible remarks," Qaicham Norbu
stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
