<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Samaranch Re-elected as IOC President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The 77-year-old Juan Antonio
Samaranch was re-elected by a unanimous vote Thursday as president
of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) for a fourth term
until year of 2001.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch first took the spot in 1980 and was originally due to
retire this year under IOC rules preventing members standing for
office after the age of 75.
</P>
<P>
But he was able to stay in power after his Latin allies forced
a vote to raise the IOC age limit in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch has played a huge role in turning the Olympic
movement into a successful commercial enterprise and earlier this
year signed a television deal for more than two billion
U.S. dollars with the American network NBC for the 2004 and 2008
Summer Games and 2006 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch has already said that this will be his last period in
office and that the 2000 Sydney Summer Olympics will mark his last
Games in charge.
</P>
<P>
He has also said that he would not hesitate to step down at any
time if he felt he was not fit enough to continue in office.
</P>
<P>
The IOC session also elected American Anita Defrantz as its
first woman vice-president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
