<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Contributes to World Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- China has led the world with
average annual economic growth of 12 percent over the past five
years, some 8.6 percentage points higher than the world average.
</P>
<P>
China continues to maintain a rapid economic growth which is
expected to hit 10 percent for 1997, according to a recent report
released by the State Statistical Bureau.
</P>
<P>
China has jumped to 7th place in the world now from 10th place
in 1990 in terms of GDP, with the nation becoming one of the major
driving forces fueling the economic recovery throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the central government has adopted a moderately
tight macroeconomic control policy designed to balance reform,
development and stability, while at the same time cooling the
overheated economy and reducing double-digit inflation.
</P>
<P>
As a consequence, China has successfully fulfilled its targets
for an economic "soft landing" and has managed to record continued
stable economic performance.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 20 years, China has made marked advances in
promoting its overall national strength and established close
links with the world economy.
</P>
<P>
China, home to world's largest population, continues to play an
increasingly important role in worldwide economic development. In
addition, China holds an important position in the world trade,
capital, and tourist markets.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign trade volume reached 289.9 billion US dollars
in 1996, ranking 11th in the world, with export volume reaching
151.1 billion US dollars. China expects to maintain a growing GDP,
and has vast potential for developing imports and exports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Contributes to World Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The nation's foreign currency reserves of more than 120 billion
US dollars, the second largest in the world, will also guarantee
more foreign trade business.
</P>
<P>
China has led developing countries in the use of long-term
overseas capital since the 1990s, and is currently the world's
second largest user of foreign funds following the United States.
</P>
<P>
Recent estimates indicate that well over half the world's top
500 multinational corporations have listed China as their first
choice for investment.
</P>
<P>
China has rapidly increased personnel exchanges with countries
throughout the world. Last year alone, China hosted more than 51
million overseas visitors, or 8.6 percent of the worldwide total,
ranking second only to France. The nation's tourism earnings for
the year hit 12 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The growing output of China's major agricultural and industrial
products have contributed greatly to a stable world market. In
1996, China ranked first in the world in producing cereals,
cotton, rapeseed, meat, steel, coal, textiles, cement, and TV
sets, and second in power output and chemical fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
The fact that China feeds the 22 percent of global population
on only seven percent of the total farmland readily exhibits that
China is a major contributor to the world economy, according to
the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Township Enterprises in China Absorb Half of Surplus Rural Laborers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 5 (Xinhua) -- By the end of 1996, China's
23 million township enterprises had employed 135 million people,
about half of the surplus labor force in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
Township industries have played a big role in the country's
industrialization and economic development as a whole.
</P>
<P>
This conclusion was made by participants at a recent
international seminar on a comparative study of township
enterprises in China and small and medium-sized firms in
Japan. The meeting was held in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The countryside in China has a dense population and limited
cultivated land. In the early 1990s, the country's surplus rural
labor force reached 250 million, while the farmland per capita was
less than 0.093 ha.
</P>
<P>
The booming rural industries have provided a way out for the
country's excess rural workers. Between 1978-1988, the number of
laborers hired by township enterprises went up by 6.72 million
annually. In 1989, the figure topped 93.66 million, which
accounted for 22 percent of the village workforce in China.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, the number of workers in township enterprises, which
stood at 112 million, surpassed that of state-owned enterprises
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Township industries account for one third of farmers'
income. The payroll of the workers in township firms came to 534
billion yuan (65 billion US dollars) in 1996, and the annual
average wage was 4,195 yuan (511 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Seminar participants spoke highly of the development of rural
industries since the country adopted the reform and opening policy
in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Xie Baisan from Fudan University observed that an
ever-growing army of industrial workers has emerged in the
countryside, which has profound implications for China. The state
would have to pay over three trillion yuan to employ these surplus
laborers, but the cost is 200 billion yuan when they are hired by
rural enterprises, the professor noted.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the state has not had to earmark funds to arrange
employment for the surplus rural workforce, thanks to the
township and village-based factories.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
