<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are some
major economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the
past few days:
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuelan net income from oil exports reached 9.13
billion U.S. dollars from January to July this year.
</P>
<P>
Experts foresee that the net income for the whole year will
surpass 15 billion dollars if quotations stability in the
international market is maintained.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentine cement output will grow 30 percent in
1997 compared to the previous year, according to a report from
U.S. consulting firm Santander Investment about the performance of
the sector.
</P>
<P>
Argentina will produce 6.7 million tons of cement this year, an
increase of 1.6 million tons from that of 1996.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico's mining industry has invested over 1
billion U.S. dollars so far this year in exploitation, acquisition
and replacement of equipment, a Commerce Ministry report said.
</P>
<P>
The firms that make up the Mexican Mining Chamber committed
themselves to investing 5.147 billion dollars during the 1995-2000
period, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- The Colombian economy will grow 3 percent
this year as forecast by the Duff and Phelps risk rating company.
</P>
<P>
"The growth will be 3 percent, which is positive. However,
Colombia fulfills all the conditions for a bigger growth," said
Gustavo Aristizabal, president of the firm.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean wine exports earned the country 202.8
million dollars in the first seven months of this year, a 41.3
percent increase over the same period of 1996, informed the
Chilean Association of Exporters and Bottlers of Wine.
</P>
<P>
The average export price for Chilean wine has increased from
1.59 dollars per liter last year to 1.95 dollars per liter this
year.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaraguan exports will generate 850 million dollars
this year, a 20 percent increase over what registered in 1996,
said the Exports and Investments Center (CEI).
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The Costa Rican municipalities collected 12 million
dollars in taxes on real estate during the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
A report published by the Municipal Promotion and Counseling
Institute says that if the trend continues some 24 million dollars
in taxes could be collected from the real estate sector.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguayan trade deficit reached 1.013 billion
dollars in the 12 months ended in May.
</P>
<P>
Data released today by the Central Bank of Uruguay show that
exports were 2.525 billion while imports stood at 3.538 billion
dollars in the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
