<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, September 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan condemned Thursday's suicide bomb explosions in
downtown West Jerusalem that killed at least seven people,
including three suspected Hamas bombers, and wounded 165 others.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's King Hussein made a telephone call Thursday evening to
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to condemn the bombings,
saying Jordan is against such a terrorist action.
</P>
<P>
The explosions prompted the Israeli government to reimpose the
total closure on West Bank and Gaza Strip which has been partially
eased during the past weeks. (Jordan-Israel-Reaction)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on Thursday condemned
bombings at a downtown Jerusalem shopping mall, saying it was not
"tolerated."
</P>
<P>
Speaking from his vacation resort in Martha's Vineyard, Mass.,
Clinton declared that Secretary of State Madeleine Albright would
go as scheduled to the Middle East next week and would take with
her the message "that terror will not be tolerated."
(U.S.-Reaction-Jerusalem Bombings)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The Queen of Britain is to make a televised broadcast
to the nation on Friday evening prior to the funeral of Princess
Diana, Buckingham Palace announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by the Duke of Edinburgh, Queen Mother and Princess
Margaret, she will fly to London on Friday morning from Balmoral,
Scotland, 18 hours earlier than planned. (UK-Queen-Diana)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus Thursday expressed satisfaction with
statement by German's Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel on Cyprus'
prospects for accession to the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman made the statement at his daily press
briefing here after Kinkel held a meeting with his visiting
Cypriot counterpart Ioannis Kasoulides in Bonn Wednesday. Kinkel
was quoted as saying that Cyprus-EU accession talks will begin as
agreed, six months after the end of the Intergovernmental
Conference. (Cyprus-Germany)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesia has agreed to purchase 12 Sukhoi 30k jet
fighters and eight MI-17-IV helicopters from Russia for a total
of 500 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Under a counter-purchase agreement, Russia has agreed to buy
from Indonesia 40 kinds of commodities which are also worth 500
million U.S. dollars, State Minister for Development Planning
Ginandjar Kartasasmita said here Thursday. (Indonesia-Russia-Jet
Fighters)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States is asking Japan to cut aid to
Cambodia in an attempt to increase pressure on Cambodian leaders
until what it called "democracy" is restored.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Secretary of State Stanley Roth told a Senate hearing
Thursday that he is going to Japan and Southeast Asian countries
next week to try to thwart millions of aid.
</P>
<P>
Japan, Cambodia's largest donor, in effect suspended aid by
recalling its aid workers after Hun Sen ousted First Prime
Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh early in July. (US-Cambodia-Roth)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States will send more F-16 jet
fighters to form a special force to help the NATO-led
Stabilization Force in Bosnia during the municipal elections on
September 13 and 14, the Pentagon said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the decision at a regular briefing, Michael
Doubleday, a Pentagon spokesman, said that six F-16s will fly from
Spangdahlem in Germany to join 12 F-16s in Aviano Air Base in
Italy for Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
He said that the 18 F-16s will form a special U.S. Air
Expeditionary Force in Aviano on September 8-22. The temporary
force will be joined by U.S. KC-135 refueling planes and C-130
cargo aircraft from bases in Britain. (US-Bosnia-Deployment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The World Bank/IMF Development Committee
announced Thursday that Morocco's Minister of Finance, Commerce,
Industry and Handicrafts Driss Jettou has been selected as its new
chairman.
</P>
<P>
Driss Jettou will replace Mohamed Kabbaj, who chaired the
committee from April 1995 until leaving the post as Morocco's new
finance minister last month.
</P>
<P>
The Development Committee is the joint ministerial committee of
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and also
regarded as the policy-making body of the two international
financial institutions, focused specifically on developing country
issues. (WB-IMF-Committee) 
</P>
