<HEADLINE> China Builds More Botanical Gardens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 5 (Xinhua) -- China is currently home to 120
botanical gardens, up dramatically from eight some 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
China is, in fact, a leading country in Asia in terms of the
introduction of botanical gardens, official sources said here.
</P>
<P>
The nation's botanical gardens house more than 13,000 species
of Chinese plants and receives well over 10 million visitors
annually.
</P>
<P>
China is in the process of establishing a conservation network
to transplant endangered plant species to safe areas, with current
efforts centering on the transplantation of 50-odd rare plants.
</P>
<P>
Plans also call for the establishment of a state-level seed
gene bank for endangered rare plants.
</P>
<P>
China's botanical gardens have established ties and conducted
academic exchanges with counterparts in a number of foreign
countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
