<HEADLINE> Dengue Epidemic Threatens Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Panama is threatened by a
hemorrhagic dengue epidemic like the one Costa Rica is going
through, a Health Ministry official warned today.
</P>
<P>
Manuel Vazquez, general director of health in the Health
Ministry said, "We must learn from what is going on in Costa Rica,
Guatemala, Nicaragua and other countries of the Central American
isthmus, where there have been epidemics with a sequel of sick and
dead persons."
</P>
<P>
He said that since 1993 mosquitos, the carrier of the deadly
dengue virus, have thrived in Panama.
</P>
<P>
The country has registered 5,170 cases of dengue since 1993,
which are alarming if the population of the country, 2 million, is
taken into account.
</P>
<P>
Vazquez called on the citizens to destroy mosquito breeding
places and take other measures to prevent an epidemic in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
