<HEADLINE> Italy Urges Continuation of Middle East Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Italian leaders today stressed
the importance of continuing the Middle East peace process despite
the latest attacks by suicide bombers that left at least eight
dead and some 150 others wounded in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued to the press, Italian Prime Minister
Romano Prodi expressed condolences for the victims and reaffirmed
"Italy's strong support for the peace process, in the belief that
its continuation will lead to the definitive defeat of the
criminal authors of these repugnant attacks."
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on the same issue, Italian Foreign
Minister Lamberto Dini said the peace process had been "too slow"
in the last months, leaving room for extremists to "re-emerge."
</P>
<P>
He called for greater efforts from Europe and the United States
to revive the momentum of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
In a message to Israeli President Ezer Weizman, Italian
President of State Oscar Luigi Scalfaro said the latest wave of
"barbarous" attacks "proves once again the need to break the cruel
logic of terror and hatred and continue with courage and
determination on the path to peace."
</P>
<P>
Israeli police sources are reported as saying in Jerusalem that
eight people, including three suicide bombers, have been killed
and about 150 wounded in the attacks at the main Ben-Yehuda
shopping center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
