<HEADLINE> Roth to Prevent Japan From Resuming Aid to Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States is asking
Japan to cut aid to Cambodia in an attempt to increase pressure on
Cambodian leaders until what it called "democracy" is restored.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Secretary of State Stanley Roth told a Senate hearing
today that he is going to Japan and Southeast Asian countries next
week to try to thwart millions of aid.
</P>
<P>
"I'm going to Japan next week with the specific purpose to try
to ensure that Japan does not have a full-scale resumption of its
aid program," he told the Senate Foreign Relations panel.
</P>
<P>
Japan, Cambodia's largest donor, in effect suspended aid by
recalling its aid workers after Hun Sen ousted First Prime
Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh early in July.
</P>
<P>
Roth said he would push "very hard" during his Tokyo stop on
September 12 and 13 to prevent the return of aid workers other
than those involved in the humanitarian projects of
non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
Roth said he will also travel to the Philippines and Indonesia,
which he said might influence Cambodia through the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations.
</P>
<P>
He told the Senate panel the Clinton administration continues
to count on the Association of Southeast Asian Nations to lead
negotiations to resolve the Cambodia crisis.
</P>
<P>
Roth said the United States is continuing to suspend some 60
million dollars in assistance other than humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
Roth will leave Washington Friday and will stop in the
Philippines, South Korea and Japan before returning home on
September 14.
</P>
<P>
Roth's nomination as assistant secretary of state for East
Asian and Pacific affairs was approved a month ago by the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
