<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Voting on Compulsory Retirement Savings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Post office staff began to
distribute referendum packs throughout New Zealand today, kicking
off a 20-day national referendum on the compulsory retirement
savings scheme (RSS).
</P>
<P>
NZ Post said 2.5 million packs will be sent to households in
NZ's first postal referendum on RSS at a cost of 5.1 million NZ
dollars (3.15 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The RSS, the brainchild of Deputy Prime Minister Winston
Peters, has attracted attention from the public. The office
overseeing the referendum said a few days ago that over 93
percent of the eligible voters had registered with it and that the
percentage was even higher than that in the last general
election.
</P>
<P>
Presenting his scheme in July, Winston Peters maintained that
the present universal superannuation is not sustainable with the
growing population of old people. He estimated that the
superannuation, now costing NZ the equivalent of 5 percent of
gross domestic product, will rise to almost 12 percent by 2059.
</P>
<P>
He argued that the government will need to raise either tax
rates or the age of entitlement, or reduce the amount of pension
to pay superannuation.
</P>
<P>
Under his scheme, all people earning over 5,000 NZ dollars
(3,150 US dollars) a year must pay a percentage of their income
into a private sector retirement fund.
</P>
<P>
The target of their savings is 120,000 NZ dollars if people
start saving from the age of 25. Once they reach 65, they will use
the money to buy an annuity. But those are not able to save up to
the target will get a top-up from the government.
</P>
<P>
In the past two months since the RSS was put up, Television NZ
has run a series of programs to answer questions concerning the
scheme.
</P>
<P>
But the scheme has met strong opposition from many social
sectors, particularly from poor people. The opposition said the
poor people will fare even worse if they set aside a certain
amount of money for RSS.
</P>
<P>
While the rich think it unnecessary for them to save. They feel
uneasy to put the money into private fund while they cannot touch
the money before they reach 65.
</P>
<P>
Even in the parliament, a recent survey showed that two thirds
of the MPs were against the RSS. Opposing MPs believe that NZ has
the basis of sound retirement provision in the current
superannuation scheme.
</P>
<P>
But supporters of the scheme warn of the increasing pressures
an aging population will exert on the economy over the next 40
years, and point to the fillip which the economy will get from
compulsory savings.
</P>
<P>
Whatever their opinion, people must cast their vote before
September 26, and the final results are expected to be announced
on October 1.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
