<HEADLINE> Free Trade Fails to Make Canadian Economy More Efficient </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Free trade has failed to make
Canadian manufacturers more efficient, according to a report by a
Canadian investment firm.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian factories have remained competitive with U.S.
factories only because the Canadian dollar has weakened
substantially since 1991.
</P>
<P>
Productivity levels in Canadian factories were only 80 percent
of those in U.S. factories last year, compared with 95 percent in
1994 and 87 percent in 1988.
</P>
<P>
"Such performance runs counter to the very raison d'etre for
free trade," said the report, which was prepared by CIBC Woody
Gundy Securities Inc. and was published today.
</P>
<P>
"Unfettered access to huge American markets was supposed to
wipe out Canada's productivity disadvantage by allowing Canadian
producers to achieve scale economies otherwise unobtainable in a
small and fragmented domestic market," it said.
</P>
<P>
It should also have pressured manufacturers to become more
efficient so they could compete not only for U.S. customers, but
also against U.S. competitors here at home.
</P>
<P>
Yet, it said, "the competitive pressures that the loss of trade
protection would have normally brought have been blunted and in
most cases actually reversed by the Canadian dollar's
depreciation."
</P>
<P>
Only three industries, namely leather, furniture and clothing,
have been exposed to tariff cuts under free trade that exceeded
the 12 percent depreciation in the Canadian dollar against the
U.S. currency during the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
"The other 12 manufacturing sectors are effectively more
protected today than they were before the free trade, with tariff
cuts swamped by the impact of a depreciating exchange rate," the
report noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
