<HEADLINE> US to Attack Canada in New Dairy War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States is set to
attack Canada's dairy industry again as Canadian dairy farmers
find new buyers for their products abroad, said a report today.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is setting the stage for a complaint to the World
Trade Organization about Canada's new two-tiered milk pricing
system, the Financial Post newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The two-year-old pricing system allows Canadian food producers
to buy milk more cheaply if their products are exported.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Canada exported 243 million U.S. dollars' worth of dry
milk powder, butter and cheese to 80 countries.
</P>
<P>
Since the system came into place, Canada's trade balance in
dairy products has gone from a deficit of 8.6 million dollars to a
surplus of 36.5 million dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. National Milk Producers Federation is complaining that
Canada is replacing export subsidies, soon to become illegal, with
"carefully camouflaged subsidies."
</P>
<P>
The federation was reported to be preparing a detailed report
on the Canadian pricing system that will be the basis of a formal
complaint to the WTO later this year.
</P>
<P>
U.S. trade negotiators looked into more details about the
system here recently.
</P>
<P>
Canada dismissed the U.S. complaints about the pricing system,
saying the system is allowed under international trade rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
