<DOCNO> XIE19970905.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One in Four Americans Poorly Manage Debts: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 4 (Xinhua) -- At a time when consumer
spending is at its all-time-high, one in four Americans believes
they have debt management problems, according to a national
survey.
</P>
<P>
However, the same study revealed that 91 percent of Americans
believe they are good money managers -- grading themselves a "C"
or better on their ability to manage their finances.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted by Omnibus Consumer Survey by the
Opinion Research Corporation International.
</P>
<P>
"When counseling thousands of consumers in financial distress
each week, we have found that most don't recognize their lack of
money management skills until faced with a financial crisis,"
said Bernie Dancel, founder and CEO of the National Credit
Counceling Services.
</P>
<P>
The fact is there is a serious consumer debt problem, and
everyone could benefit from going "back to school" to learn the
ABC's of budgeting and handling credit, said Dancel, whose company
receives hundreds of calls a week about debt management.
</P>
<P>
Among those polled, nearly 50 percent state they would be
stronger money managers if they could improve their financial
skills through training. The study also revealed that nearly half
of American families do not believe that they received adequate
money management training.
</P>
<P>
Consumer debt has soared 39 percent in the last five years and
now exceeds 1 trillion U.S. dollars, according to the Consumer
Credit Delinquency Bulletin. For every dollar of income earned
over the past five years, consumers spend 1.10 U.S. dollars. That
has helped push consumer debt to record levels and has resulted in
record debt, delinquencies and bankruptcies, according to
researchers involved in the survey.
</P>
<P>
Last year, more than 1 million consumers filed for personal
bankruptcies, discharging 30 billion U.S. dollars in consumer
debt. This translates to 300 U.S. dollars for every American
household. Those losses are passed on to all consumers in the form
of higher interest rates and higher prices for goods and services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
