<HEADLINE> US Deploys Special Air Force in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States will send
more F-16 jet fighters to form a special force to help the
NATO-led Stabilization Force (SFOR) in Bosnia during the municipal
elections on September 13 and 14, the Pentagon said today.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the decision at a regular briefing, Michael
Doubleday, a Pentagon spokesman, said that six F-16s will fly from
Spangdahlem in Germany to join 12 F-16s in Aviano Air Base in
Italy for Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the 18 F-16s will form a special U.S.
Air Expeditionary Force in Aviano on September 8-22. The temporary
force will be joined by U.S. KC-135 refueling planes and C-130
cargo aircraft from bases in Britain.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first deployment of the Air Expeditionary Force
in a European Theater by the U.S. Air Force. Such a force was
deployed temporarily in the past in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
"This is a part of the overall picture, which is one of
measures ensuring that people on the ground realize that there is
a NATO (the North Atlantic Treaty Organization) presence. It
includes not only the SFOR troops but air assets also," he said.
</P>
<P>
"These aircraft will play a role overhead in Bosnia of ensuring
that the environment on the ground remains such that people can
get to the polling places and vote," Doubleday added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) said it plans to go ahead with the
elections in Bosnia despite a sometimes-violent political struggle
in Bosnian Serb territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
