<HEADLINE> Chicago Students Required to Do Community Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Chicago's public high
school students will be required to join a growing number of
youths across the United States to do community service before
their graduation, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
Starting with the class of 1999, they'll have to put in 60
hours of work during their four years to earn their diplomas, Paul
Vallas, the school system's chief executive officer, was quoted
by the Associated Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
Vallas said the requirement would instill "values, ethics and
morals" into the mind of the young people.
</P>
<P>
The community service includes working at nursing homes,
day-care centers, hospitals and tutoring younger students.
</P>
<P>
"There's no better way to teach and reinforce these things than
to have children perform community service," Vallas said.
</P>
<P>
Similar policies are in place in many communities across the
country. Some 50 seniors were prevented from graduation last May
by such a policy in Maryland state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
