<HEADLINE> Internet Telephony Catches Industry Attention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 4 (Xinhua) -- More people are retrieving
their voice mail and returning voice messages via laptops in
remote locations such as hotel rooms around the world for the cost
of a local phone call.
</P>
<P>
This is the result of the fast development of Internet
telephony, a hot product in telecommunications, according to Jeff
Pulver, president of Pulver.com, a major player in the industry.
Pulver believes 1997 is the year of the Telecommunications
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of companies with Internet telephony offerings will
participate in the world's largest public demonstration which will
be held Monday, September 22, 1997 at the World Trade Center in
Boston. These companies will be showcasing their products'
compatibility and interoperability.
</P>
<P>
The Internet Protocol (IP) Voice Strategy can save people,
especially companies, a large amount of money, experts said. "It
is not a question of when, but rather how, your business is going
to be affected by the Voice On the Net(TM) (VON) industry," Pulver
said.
</P>
<P>
"Quality Internet Telephony is real and readily available,"
Pulver said.
</P>
<P>
Internet telephony software, hardware and service companies
including IBM, Intel, Lucent, Microsoft and VocalTec have agreed
upon Internet telephony standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
