<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Ruling Parties Pledge to Hold on to Euro Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 4 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
Christian Democratic Union (CDU) and its sister party Christian
Social Union (CSU) today agreed to hold on to the planned 1999
launch of the single European currency with strict adherence to
the qualification criteria.
</P>
<P>
The common position was reached by the CDU and the CSU during
their so-called strategy summit today in Kloster Andechs in the
southern German state of Bavaria.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the meeting, German Finance Minister and CSU
leader Theo Waigel expressed optimism that Germany would be able
to reduce its budget deficit to 2.9 percent of the gross domestic
product (GDP) by the end of this year, which is better than the
3.0-percent limit required for Euro membership.
</P>
<P>
During the summit, which is also attended by Kohl, the two
ruling parties also agreed to continue to seek compromise with the
main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) on tax and pension
reforms. Moreover, they also agreed to focus attention on job
creation and combating crimes in the run-up to the next general
elections due in September 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
